INSERT INTO `mog_synthesis` VALUES ('1', '6', '171', '2015', 'Various crop and livestock-related CSA technologies and practices were tested and evaluated across the CSVs in East Africa. These included crop diversification - cassava (drought, mosaic-tolerant varieties, lower soil fertility) - IITA; Drought-tolerant (DT) maize (CIMMYT); DT/rust-tolerant common bean and Soil fertility management  (CIAT); Low moisture tolerant pigeon pea (ICRISAT); Grain storage (CIMMYT); Push and pull (ICIPE); Forage (bracharia) (ICIPE/CIAT); Galla goats and Red-Masaai Sheep with faster growth rates, early maturing and tolerant to worms, and Sweet potato vines for livestock feed (ILRI); Beans, including drought-tolerant, locally adapted varieties (Bioversity). In some cases, these were guided by climate information (e.g. in Nyando and Lushoto), including indigenous knowledge. Seed source suitability maps for important tree species selection in East Africa were developed by ICRAF. In Ethiopia, ICRAF and CIAT through the P4S project has been working with the government to prioritize context specific CSA options for scaling up CSA.', 'On-farm and on-station field events and activities ensured gender and social inclusion. Evaluation of the CSA options in Nyando were spearheaded by CBOs, whose membership consists of 60% women. Gender desegregated data from some of the trials being collected/analysed by CIMMYT and Bioversity. Linkages to CIMMYT SIMLESA project provided extra funds for social inclusion in AIPs. The selected priority tree species by ICRAF can benefit various end users including women, youth and marginalized communities. The CSA prioritization framework identifies gender as an outcome in the qualitative matrix developed in collaboration with World Vision and used in the NEPAD practical guide.'), ('2', '6', '174', '2015', 'A participatory content development programme for sms rolled out in Tanzania through the SIMLESA project. ClimMob 2.0, an online platform for CSA citizen science is available online (www.climmob.net), to be launched in April 2016. The Climate Wizard has been updated to incorporate the CMIP5 GCMs, and outputs integrated into CSA National Framework Programs in five African Countries. Also, a draft version of an interactive web mapping tool has been developed to support the Africa CSA Alliance planning efforts (http://nkoech.github.io/africacsa/). The Global Yield Gap Atlas is now fully functional, contributing to innovative knowledge management system and decision support and dissemination tool.', 'On-going follow up studies in three sites of AGMARK\'s work shows that out of the 1.5 million scaling materials distributed, 30% reached women-led households. All PEACSA research activities have prioritised gender disaggregation in focus group discussions, farmer field days and farm typology work. For ClimMob 2.0, data collected were disaggregated by gender, with a manual written in a gender-inclusive language, emphasizing the importance of participation of women and men.'), ('3', '6', '172', '2015', 'PEACSA applied decision support tools for CSA prioritisation for local adaptation and the AgMIP integrated assessments are being used for CSA prioritization. Future seed zonation maps developed by ICRAF are available to guide decision making, while the tree fodder nutrition databases will be used in feeds and forages priority setting. Draft LAPA for Nyando developed, to be validated in 2016 with potential of inclusion in county agricultural development plans. Weighted means and Bayesian networks algorithms for targeting CSA developed (P4S project), and piloted with Tanzania Ministry of Agriculture, Livestock, and Fisheries and ACSAA partners. In Uganda, a study on local knowledge on pests and diseases and comparison with expert knowledge and measurements in the field conducted in Mount Elgon,. A shade tree advise tool developed and framework for planning climate smart coffee presented to the coffee sector. Analysis on socio-economical trade-off of CSA practices in coffee regions in Uganda ongoing.', 'Gender desegregated data collected by CIMMYT, including Rural Household Multiple Indicator Survey data by Bioversity. Gender dimensions also included in AGMIP analyses, despite data limitations. Youth and women in Nyando will be involved in validation of draft local adaptation plan. Women coordinate local farmer learning events, where women lead village demonstrations for knowledge sharing. Selected priority tree species can benefit a wide range of end-users, including women, youth and marginalized communities. The shade tree advice tool takes into consideration specific needs of farmers, including women. Gender also considered in both Weighted means and Bayesian networks targeting methods by ICRAF/CIAT.'), ('4', '6', '175', '2015', 'ICRAF, CIAT and CCAFS EA supported the development of National CSA Framework Programs in 5 African countries - Kenya, Tanzania, Uganda, Botswana and Namibia. These framework programs provide the framework for scaling CSA within the countries, and a basis for developing large funding proposals (e.g. GCF), and integration into INDCs and sub-national implementation plans.Context specific data on tree fodder utilization have been assembled and complemented with data on tree fodder nutritional qualities.', 'P4S has worked with researchers Royal Galloway University to develop CSA gender indicators for use in the CSA Profiles being developed for six African countries and the CCAFS CSA Prioritization Framework.Gender roles on fodder management will be explored/elaborated in reports on fodder tree utilization.'), ('5', '6', '173', '2015', 'A systems framework that will plan for climate smart coffee/cocoa regions developed. PEACSA worked closely with CCAFS EA, especially in CSV to test CSA technologies. Formation of AIP initiated in Wote with seven farmer groups (hosting CSA trials) - establishment in 2016, and enhancing the role of agri-business in scaling CSA (CCAFS working paper https://cgspace.cgiar.org/rest/bitstreams/60041/retrieve). A systems framework developed that will have coffee/cocoa sector to plan for climate smart coffee/cocoa regions.', 'Gender is mentioned in the systems framework as an important \"factor\" in order to for example increase adoption of CSA technologies. An inclusive AIP is will be established in Wote in mid 2016 by PEACSA.'), ('6', '6', '46', '2015', 'Several climate forecasting and down-scaling tools were evaluated by ICPAC. ICPAC also selected tools that improved seasonal forecasts and allow for further processing of the forecasts. As a result, ICPAC has been able to convert probabilistic rainfall forecasts into rainfall amounts which are useful for national climate service providers.', 'NA'), ('7', '6', '47', '2015', 'NA', 'NA'), ('8', '6', '50', '2015', 'NA', 'NA'), ('9', '6', '49', '2015', 'The DSSAT model has been calibrated using data collected from previous experiments, and agricultural sample surveys. The model has been tested to simulate national yields of maize and sorghum in Ethiopia and Kenya using gridded climate and soil data at high resolution.', 'NA'), ('10', '6', '48', '2015', 'No progress made in East Africa in 2015.', 'NA'), ('11', '6', '41', '2015', 'A systematic review to assess the scientific evidence and private sector experience with regard to “ready to adopt best climate-smart dairy management practices” completed, taking into account fodder production, feeding practices, animal health and breeding. Also, a review was undertaken to identify existing financing mechanisms within the dairy sector. Development of the aspirational mitigation target for agriculture calculations of potential of sustainable intensification and other methodologies for helping agriculture meet the 2-degree target. Analysis of mitigation in INDCs developed for COP21, and shows 103 countries pledging mitigation in agriculture. Development and dissemination of v2 of CCAFS-Mitigation Options Tool. Consultations with EADD partner Heifer and local Nandi stakeholders on site/intervention sampling strategy for Kenya Dairy NAMA undertaken.', 'Mitigation practices (improved feed quality, animal health and husbandry, manure management, grazing management) to reduce CH4 and N2O emissions in dairy supply chains of EA were analysed on their potential impact on gender equity and social justice among smallholder livestock farmers. An analysis to understand the current gender differentiated roles in dairy production, to inform future analysis of how changes in dairy production to reduce GHG emissions will have an impact on women\'s duties and responsibilities is on-going. In addition, analysis of inclusion of gender in mitigation and adaptation plans included in INDCs.'), ('12', '6', '40', '2015', 'National level targeting strategy for selecting geographic locations for collecting data developed, in order to develop estimates of emissions (current) and future reductions through targeted interventions. A sampling strategy for collecting emissions data from smallholder dairy systems at county level also developed and implemented, and data collection for feed/ manure interventions initiated. Low-cost measurement methods for quantification of GHGs available online (SAMPLES). Database for Tier-2 emission factors measured by CCAFS and partners (SAMPLES) created and disseminated. Training provided for 8 PhD scientists from developing countries to study GHG emissions from agriculture through CLIFF Network.', '6 of the 8 CLIFF students in 2015 were women.'), ('13', '6', '42', '2015', 'Reviews of the economics of AWD in paddy rice, balanced N fertilizer use, and monitoring, reporting and verification directory for climate finance compiled and disseminated via LEDS Global Partnership Finance meeting, World Bank, CCAC Technical support and advising to CCAC, IFAD, USAID, WB. Collaboration with GCF, NAMA Facility, private sector ongoing.', 'Additional outputs included reviews of opportunities to improve women’s participation in and benefits from LED in paddy rice in Vietnam, dairy in Kenya and livestock in Costa Rica. Also includes a synthesis of equity implications of carbon markets for smallholder farmers in East Africa.'), ('14', '6', '176', '2015', 'Two national policies, including the Kenya Agricultural Policy, one sector strategy (ASSP)) and one regional policy (EAC Forest Management and Protection Bill) were reviewed. Scenarios were used to review one national policy (NEP) and the ASSP. Results of the PACCA policy analysis and stakeholder workshops shared with learning alliances (LAs) and targeted forums prompting engagement actions by LAs. Climate-smart Agriculture Framework Programs (CSA-FPs) developed in 5 African countries - Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania, Botswana and Namibia - through CGIAR technical support, including supporting preparation of the Kenya INDC. A scoping study has been completed on science-policy-practice interface in climate change adaptation ILRI, outlining  actual national policy processes, including formulation and implementation. Scenario-guided policy processes in EA included Tanzania’s Socio-Economic Development plan.', 'Gender gaps in policies were identified and findings from participatory workshops were shared in LAs. A framework is being developed to plan for gender inclusion in policies. LAs members planned for a high level engagement, with M&E results requiring LAs to increase women participation. Youth from CSVs participated in the Youth Conference on CBA9 in April, and the outcome statement prepared presented at COP 21. Also, CCAFS scientists reviewed the gender goal in the Sustainable Development Goals. Scoping study on science-policy-practice interface in climate change adaptation identified relevant gender and social inclusions issues to be pursued in follow up research.'), ('15', '6', '179', '2015', 'Oxford University CCAFS researchers were among the authors of the UNEP GEO6; • WWF used SEA scenario for ADB investment; SPC owner of Pacific scenarios; collaboration with UNDP in Bangladesh NAP; CSA 101 contribution; UNFCCC SBSTA; Major DFID outcome case. The tool developed within the \"Multi-disciplinary species distribution modeling – climate change impact projection and adaptation planning with climatic, environmental and socioeconomic factors\" project is generalizable and flexible, making it appropriate for large-scale decision-making across SSA.', 'Gender balance, as well as the representation of vulnerable groups, was always taken into account in workshop process design with the \"CCAFS scenario-guided policy and investment planning\" project.'), ('16', '6', '178', '2015', 'African Group of Negotiators (AGN) supported to prepare submissions on integration of agriculture into UNFCCC global climate change discussions. Three submissions made on Early Warning Systems; Risks and Vulnerability in Agricultural Systems; Gender and Climate Change. A scoping study on science-policy-practice interface in climate change adaptation completed, outlining  actual national policy processes, including formulation and implementation. Interactions organized between AU Commission and key national level actors (engaged, cumulatively, in climate change adaptation, genetic resource conservation and sustainable use, and domestication of multilateral environmental agreements) from many African countries, culminating in a decision that AU Commission/CCAFS will develop policy/guidelines in 2016/17.', 'AGN and civil society groups supported to prepare submissions on gender and climate change to the UNFCCC during SBSTA 42 in June 2015. The policy/guidelines will highlight the importance of social inclusion and provide examples for how national programs can put inclusive systems in place to allow women and men, and socially marginalized people within countries, to take advantage of the ITPGRFA for climate change adaptation.'), ('17', '6', '177', '2015', 'Climate change mainstreamed in district development plans (DDPs) in two districts, including integration of policy actions to address implementation issues. Through adaptation planning process, these districts selected CSA based on agro-ecological zones. The district learning alliances engage on policy actions that address implementation challenges at local level. First data analysis using database of 13k+ farm households completed within the ILRI-led \"What works where for which farmer project\". Rapid multi-indicator survey tool developed and applied in 4 contrasting systems in developing countries. Spatial maps generated of farming systems and key patterns in drivers of household level food security for Uganda.', 'Context specific gender issues were identified during the zonal planning, with stakeholders developing means of addressing them. A systems approach to gender, which is used to appraise gender differences across levels highlighting context specific issues. The zonal planning approach and the systems approach to gender are new tools being developed. Gender equity is integrated within the rapid multi-indicator survey tool. First paper on the tool and analyses has been submitted. Applications are foreseen for west, central and east africa, which together with existing data will result in a global analysis of the interplay between agriculture, gender, and nutrition'), ('18', '7', '171', '2015', 'Suitable CSA options are being tested and validated in the target countries of West Africa. These include: crop rotation, water conservation techniques (tied-ridging, bunding, zai), conservation agriculture, agroforestry and the shade tree recommendation (for coffee and cocoa) which all build on traditional knowledge. Most importantly, suitability maps are developed to help decision makers to plan for CSA depending on the level of climate change. In the area of water, selected water storage options and crop-livestock interventions are being tested on the field through PAR. In Ghana and Mali, CCAFS worked with the government to prioritize context specific CSA options for scaling up CSA. CCAFS scientists have also been working with World Vision in Niger to help them mainstream CSA into their new agricultural strategy. Furthermore, a methodology to conduct the inventory and prioritization of the climate-smart crop-livestock-agroforestry practices has been developed and shared with team leaders of targeted countries.', 'In the CSV model development, CSA options specific to women have been experimented. This included non timber forest product processing (baobab fruit transformation into powder) by women small enterprise in Senegal and Casia tora growing in the Niger CSV. Also within the CSA prioritization framework, gender is listed as an outcome in the qualitative matrix developed in collaboration with World Vision which is used in the NEPAD practical guide. Furthermore, a framework similar to the coffee/cocoa CSA framework is being developed to help plan for gender specific interventions when planning for climate-smart coffee/cocoa.'), ('19', '7', '172', '2015', 'In Mali, two CSA portfolios were developed for CSA investment plan. One major agricultural investment from Helvetas swiss (NGO) already planned, based on the prioritized portfolios. The analysis of the climate-smartness of the Farmer-Managed Natural-Tree-Regeneration in Niger provides evidence of the carbon sequestration potential and its contribution to food security. Meanwhile, key information and data collection towards trade-off analyses is ongoing, business case development and trade-offs between different uses to be developed in 2016 will feed into this MOG. However, a methodology to conduct the inventory and prioritization of capacity building needs of the stakeholders (in adaptation planning to promote climate-smart agriculture) has been developed and shared with team leaders of target countries in West Africa (P34). In Senegal, a tradeoff analysis of different adaptation options is being completed.', 'Most projects in West Africa conducted a baseline survey to understand gender preference criteria for selecting agricultural interventions. In Mali, one CSA portfolio is focusing on technologies integration (synergies) at landscape level including contour bunds, improved varieties, diversification of income with fish ponds and development of rice cultivation valleys. The diversification of income with fish ponds component aims at empowering women involved in fish marketing activities. In Senegal gender dimensions were considered important in the extensive pastoralist systems in the northern part of the country.'), ('20', '7', '173', '2015', 'Several strategies are being set up to enhance adaptive capacity and resilience from the field to sub-national levels in West Africa. For example in the bid to develop business cases to support scaling out of water storage options, the need for increased water storage is being established to overcome short dry spells to increase resilience to climate variability and climate change. In Ghana, scaling pathways are identified via public policy (e.g. Forestry Commission, REDD+) and private companies while a systems framework has been developed to have the coffee/cocoa sector plan for climate smart coffee/cocoa regions. In the CSV model development there are organization of workshops, training programs and field testing of a set of climate smart technologies including: crop rotation, water conservation techniques (tied-ridging, bunding, zai), conservation agriculture and agroforestry as strategies for creating awareness and scaling up CSA options.', 'In the CSVs, three gender-sensitive projects were implemented: (1) understanding male and female farmers’ access and use of climate information in Ghana; (2) valorizing non-timber forest products for increased resilience and food security in Sénégal; (3) assessing the performance of Cassia tora and cowpea under improved zai techniques for increased resilience in Niger. The role of gender was also identified as key in the use of different water storage options and selection of water storage options supporting women and youth for business case development. In addition, inventory workshops on climate smart practices considered the participation of at least 30% women.'), ('21', '7', '174', '2015', 'Local rural radios and mobiles are used and a consortium of at least 10 partners involved in a process of 9 steps going from establishing the partnership and planning to the evaluation of the results of the activities in each site in West Africa (P34). In relation to multi-stakeholder platforms, these are established in Ghana and initial conversations convened with more than 70 people. In addition, sub-national workshops on CSA practices were held in Ghana to identify & prioritize CSA practices (P57). For learning alliances, the Climate Wizard was updated to incorporate the CMIP5 GCMs, and outputs from this were integrated into the CSA National Framework Programs in five African Countries. In addition, a draft version of an interactive web mapping tool has been developed to support the Africa CSA Alliance planning efforts (http://nkoech.github.io/africacsa/). The 10 CSVs are now effective innovation platforms that allow information sharing among multiple stakeholders (P87).', 'Inventory workshops on climate smart practices requires that 30% of the participants should be women.'), ('22', '7', '175', '2015', 'Information provided to NGOs, public and private sector actors raised concerns about climate change and is helping to frame the conversation about what needs to be done.', 'Inventory workshops on climate smart practices requires that 30% of the participants should be women.'), ('23', '7', '46', '2015', 'In Ghana and Mali, NHMS were trained to improve their skill in data quality control and analysis to generate information that is useful for the farmers on the ground. They were also introduced to work with TAMSAT on the estimation of daily rainfall through merging of satellite data with their station data (P34). ANACIM worked with CCAFS to identify major capacity needs for climate data (P90).', 'Increased awareness by NHMS and intermediaries of the different requirements of farmers of different gender and wealth and education levels, regarding climate information and communication approaches. Increased capacity of female and male farmers in pilot sites to interpret and use climate and crop information for decision making.'), ('24', '7', '47', '2015', 'In terms of capacity development on climate service technologies, NGOs (OXFAM, ADRA) and extension agents in northern Ghana received training on the PICSA approach and its use to guide farmers in their options and practices. Data were collected on the use of the approach by farmers, revealing that 97% of trainees changed their practice as a consequence. ANACIM engaged with the Union of Rural community radios to generate and disseminate downscaled weather and seasonal forecast across Senegal (90).', 'PICSA reached 6,000 farmers (of which 40% female). Composition of CoPs will ensure a minimum 30% women and 30% youth to help co-design, co-test and co-validate climate services-smart options adapted to genderized and socially-differentiated contexts.'), ('25', '7', '48', '2015', 'In relation to weather related insurance products, at least we can mention that index insurance products were designed for Northern Ghana, and a roadmap towards implementation was laid out with the Ghana Agricultural Insurance Program. In Senegal, all major index-based insurance stakeholders took part in a consultation workshop on the scaling/supporting role of mobile platforms leading to at least 3 collaborative project proposals.', 'A set of gender sensitive index insurance design materials, customized for the Northern Region of Ghana was produced. Materials were fully designed and pretested, plus local partners and logistics identified. Due to funding constraints, they have not yet been used in a full fieldwork campaign but are ready for implementation.'), ('26', '7', '49', '2015', 'In relation to the incorporation of decision support systems into national food security safety net programs, CRAFT has been improved to now include relevant West African crops besides maize, 1 new crop model (APSIM) and is ready to incorporate the preferred crop model used by Agrhymet for the region (SarraH). Data streams, protocols are developing for operational, gridded yield forecasting as activity 350 connects to AgMIP, JECAM/GEOGLAM and Sen2Agri projects.', 'The gender and social dimension is factored through AgMIP, to (i) model different farm household endowment levels through sliding input levels in agricultural models and (ii) analyse income and livelihood outcomes through socially differentiated strata.'), ('27', '7', '50', '2015', 'CCAFS worked with ANACIM to identify challenges to CIS scaling out and up and strategies for to guiding climate risk management by farmers in Senegal (WP135)', 'Specific information needs for womens, youths have been analysed.'), ('28', '7', '40', '2015', 'None reported', 'None reported'), ('29', '7', '176', '2015', 'In 2015, the project activities delivered key results, including the documentation of related climate change policy gaps, the comparative analysis and functioning of the district platforms (Ghana case study) with different leading structures in delivering the complex project outputs. In addition, ECOWAS and member-countries now effectively mainstreaming CSA into regional and national agricultural plans and policies through the CSA alliance (WACSAA) and implementation framework (https://ccafs.cgiar.org/blog/alliance-climate-smart-agriculture-launched-west-africa#.VrHKv8YrGpo), the development of country action plans (e.g. Ghana), and the design of National Plan for the Rural Sector for Burkina Faso-PNSR II (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sxxMNkvSz0o). The Mali national science-Policy dialogue Platform was able to coordinate the CSA prioritisation and to bring the 2 candidate CSA portfolio to the high level Policy makers (Members of the parliament).', 'Access and use of climate information by various social groups and women farmers were monitored along with project implementation. The Ghana national climate-smart agriculture and food security action plan has clear involvement strategy for women using the Women in Agriculture Development (WIAD) technical directorate of MoFA. Also, based on the stakeholder analysis done in 2014, all the relevant social groups are part of the policy processes, and in each country, the policy review processes were facilitated by the country men.'), ('30', '7', '177', '2015', 'The district-level scenarios provided opportunities to identify the priorities and climate- food-related concerns; gaps analysis helps to explore opportunities to improve the effectiveness of adaptation activities and flow of knowledge, experience and resources across levels, the on-going dialogues with high-level policy actors will contribute to implement the window of opportunities. During the scenario downscaling process in Burkina Faso, national staleholders were capacitated to use various socio-economic information for the PNSR formulation (P90).', 'Relevant social groups were part of the scenarios development with a good representation of women, in all the 9 district where the FS4 works.'), ('31', '7', '178', '2015', 'With the support of CCAFS, a West Africa CSA alliance and a CSA intervention Framework have been setup (P90). CCAFS is part of the team of experts assisting the AUC and the NEPAD Planning and Coordinating Agency in developing a technical guide and roadmap, drawing on a common set of analytical tools and approaches, and on what is achievable given many factors (data, skills, time) for informing current and future NAIPs as they seek to achieve the CAADP goals. Interactions between African Union Commission and key national level actors (engaged, cumulatively, in climate change adaptation, genetic resource conservation and sustainable use, and domestication of multilateral environmental agreements) were organized from a number of African countries. This culminated in a decision that AU Commission/CCAFS will develop policy/guidelines in 2016/17. Scoping studies have also outlined actual national policy processes, including formulation and implementation, providing a foundation for informed engagement toward MOG.', 'Scoping studies identified relevant gender and social inclusions issues to be pursued in follow up research. The policy/guidelines will, when drafted, highlight the importance of social inclusion and provide examples for how national programs can put inclusive systems in place to allow women and men, and socially marginalized people within countries, to take advantage of the ITPGRFA for climate change adaptation.'), ('32', '7', '179', '2015', 'Oxford University CCAFS researchers were among the authors of the UNEP GEO6; The scenario team worked with CCAFS WA to implement a project funded by UNU on socio-economic scenarios for ECOWAS strategies on agriculture and food security Under climate change context (P90).', 'Gender balance, as well as the representation of vulnerable groups, was always taken into account in workshop process design.'), ('33', '5', '171', '2015', 'Suitable CSA options are being tested and validated in the target countries of Latin-America. In Central-America beans varieties, including drought-tolerant and locally adapted varieties, are being tested, and vulnerability assessments are being done for coffee landscapes of Nicaragua and Guatemala identifying synergies with traditional knowledge and CSA options. Rice producers have identified best CSA practices in specific regions of Colombia, Nicaragua and Peru in order to support adaptation to climate change processes that lead to increase and yield and reduce of negative impacts due to climate variability. CSA prioritization framework has been implemented across scales in different locations in Latin America in order to strengthen the adaptability of the methodology to support decision makers from local (Purace Cauca-Colombia), sub-regional (Trifinio) to national (Guatemala) levels. Technologies such as drought-tolerant beans and forages varieties have been used by an indigenous community in Tolima-Colombia as climate adaptation measure combined with traditional knowledge.', 'Projects have collected gender disaggregated information, developed participatory mechanisms in which gender perspective is taken into account in order to frame approaches with the communities given their culture and considering also the implications of implementing new technologies in terms of roles.'), ('34', '5', '172', '2015', 'Innovative methods and approaches are being developed in order to address the use of technology to collect data and facilitate its analysis (citizen science data collected through RHoMIS format), to support coffee cooperatives by using an atlas to prioritize fruit and shade species to sustain shade in agroforestry coffee systems under climate change and to facilitate the understanding of the usefulness of the data analysis workflow in rice systems. Cost-benefit analysis have been developed within the CSA prioritization framework across scales considering their context-specific characteristics, in addition methods for cost-benefit analysis along coffee and cocoa value chains are under development. Guidelines on participatory local adaptation planning were developed in Los Cerrillos-Cauca CSV, in order to facilitate the process of the families involved in the process to specify their vulnerability to climate impacts, their chllenges considering socioeconomic limitations and a two-year plan to implement CSA measures to reduce climate negative impacts.', 'Survey and focus groups found that women and young people have a higher affinity and skills to use ICTs as a means of accessing information. The implementation of CSMS, or similar tools including data collection, interaction with information systems to facilitate decision-making, should strengthen the participation of women. Regarding Citizen Science project Rural Household Multiple Indicator Survey (RHoMIS) data are collected in a gender-disaggregated way and include an indicator on gender-specific control of livelihood activities / income streams.'), ('35', '5', '173', '2015', 'Data was collected to develop a manual on good adaptation practices and policy briefs for technicians and cooperatives for small coffee farmers which would be an output useful for small coffee farmers across Latin-America. Networks to engage and further scale up in Peru with coffee and cocoa producer and exporter organizations, NGOs and public sector for scaling are being developed. At CSV-level, evidence of the participatory approach to address local climate adaptation was used to implement a CSV in northern region of Colombia by a local partner and advances have been made with UNEP and FAO to implement CSV approach in other villages of their interest in Cauca and Narino departments. The CSA practice portfolio built through the prioritization framework in Guatemala is being used as a strategy to scale out the methodology through the national extension service mechanism to support technicians when recommending farmers short and mid-term CSA portfolios.', 'Local adaptation planning framework in Los Cerrillos-Cauca CSV includes participatory mechanisms to target and implement CSA practices with gender perspective since CCAFS CSV framework expects positive impact on social inclusion for agriculture dependent communities.'), ('36', '5', '174', '2015', 'Innovation and stakeholder platforms are being established to support CSV framework in Los Cerrillos-Cauca CSV and CSA prioritization of practices in coffee and cocoa value chains. Rices producers association in Peru, Nicaragua and Colombia are aware of how to make the process of managing and analyzing data more efficient through ICTs technologies and in Nicaragua technicians were trained in using the AEPS platform management system. Technicians from PROODECOP (Nicaraguan coffee cooperative) learned to develop online surveys and mobile data collection to strengthen their internal control systems and to include CSA indicators in these systems. Development of ClimMob 2.0, the online platform for CSA citizen science. Capacity building and empowerment in the implementation of CSA practices was done in Tolima, Colombia with indigenous communities vulnerable to drought events and water scarcity.', 'Survey and focus groups found that women and young people have a higher affinity and skills to use ICTs as a means of accessing information. PRODECOOP monitoring systems include gender-specific and gender-related indicators regarding CSA practices in coffee landscapes of Nicaragua. The ClimMob 2.0 online platform has been developed using a gender-inclusive language, emphasizing the importance of participation by both women and men.'), ('37', '5', '175', '2015', 'Publication on a existing climate smart investment plan to share Nicaragua and Guatemala small coffee farmers cooperatives experience with other cooperatives.Coffee and cocoa value chains development of CSA certification schemes will be done during 2016, however information provided to NGOs, public and private sector actors raised concerns about climate change and is helping to frame the conversation about what needs to be done.', 'Small coffee farmers cooperatives investment plan is being considered as the first step to establish a fertilizer processing plant for these regions, which allows poor farmers to have access to more affordable fertilizer.'), ('38', '5', '46', '2015', 'Strengthening of agroclimatic services has been supported through Local Technical Agroclimatic Committees Initiative in Colombia and the National Agroclimatic Bulletin where key agricultural sector stakeholders discuss recommendation to farmers given the forecast provided in the local and national committees. Use of historical local data to develop agroclimatic forecast using simple crop modelling that provides a set of inputs for farmers to decide specific actions to mitigate negative consequences. The recommendations are being disseminated through WhatsApp groups, email, voice messages and farmer-to-farmer communication. Actor mapping analysis is supporting food security safety nets in Guatemala by assessing the access, confidence and use of agroclimatic information.', 'Identification of roles regarding agroclimatic information is being done in order to address specific concerns based on women and men roles within the agricultural activities'), ('39', '5', '47', '2015', 'Local Technical Agroclimatic Committees Initiative provided an innovative approach for supporting the provision of equitable climate services for farmers in Colombia, through the development of local agroclimatic forecast analyzed and used by local technicians and farmers to recommend CSA practices that would mitigate negative impacts of climate extreme events. Bulletins translated to simpler language for indigenous communities in order to understan agroclimatic forecast provided in the Local Technical Agroclimatic Committee in Cauca. Low cost measurers were installed by farmers to record precipitation and understanding its usefulness in the agricultural activities.', 'Continue our work in identifying gender roles and social differentiation throughout the entire production chain of the key crops, Young people are learning how to understand climate data.'), ('40', '5', '48', '2015', 'Characterization of Crop Environments (Bean and Maize) to support the adaptation to climate variability in Colombia, which will allow selecting the best-site with the best agro-environmental condition (including climate, soil and agronomic factors) in order to have the best plant performance. Design of Index Insurance Prototype for basic grains in the Dry-Corridor. The team at IRI has developed a technical note that can be tailored/adjusted for insurance companies to adopt the product.', 'Participatory process of index insurance development included the participation of man and women farmers in order to consider both perspectives.'), ('41', '5', '49', '2015', 'RHoMIS surveys detailed information about the gender control over income streams within the households and allows for gender disaggregated analysis of several of the indicators. For the sentinel site system in SESAN (Secretariat of Nutrition and Food Security of Guatemala) a study was desgined to understand female participation in decision making processes in the sentinel site community committees.', 'The RHoMIS working paper presents the gender equity indicator that helps to understand the gender dimension in income control.'), ('42', '5', '50', '2015', 'Publication of the state of the art of climate and agroclimatic information in Colombia provided inputs on information gaps in the country to support policy formulation and decision making processes. Publication on network mapping in Colombia on how the agroclimatic information is available, through what channels and to whom is delivered, as well as the use of that information in decision making, provided inputs in order to know how to address agroclimatic services in the country considering regional and local specificities for expected impact on 4500 maize farmers and 3000 bean farmers in Colombia.', 'Actor mapping study on agroclimatic information in Colombia considered gender perspective which were done by women and men focal groups.'), ('43', '5', '40', '2015', 'Greenhouse gas emissions from improved and degraded pastures using SAMPLES methodology in Nicaragua, Colombia, Brazil, Trinidad and Tobago, and Argentina through PhD students which were trained during an intensive course led by CIAT. A polytunnel was constructed and Fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy-(FTIR)-Gasmet-DX4040 gas analyzer purchased (through collaboration with Livestock&Fish-CRP) that provides realiable GHG measurements with high precision and true multi-compound analysis capability. In CostaRica, Livestock Plus project contributed funds to increase the coverage of INTA–CATIE-FONTAGRO project to measure GHG through SF6 methods.', 'Livestock Plus project made baseline surveys conducted with some questions on gender that accounted for remunerated work. The aim is to complement available gender data with qualitative data in pilot farms from different regions in 2016.'), ('44', '5', '41', '2015', 'A NAMA Information Note (NINO) for Livestock sector in Colombia was submitted to the UNFCCC in September 2015, developed in collaboration with CCAFS/CIAT. CIAT-MAG-FITTACORI collaboration led to the approval of the Low Emission Livestock Strategy (Estrategia Nacional para el Desarrollo de la Ganadería Baja en Carbono, ENDGBC) in Costa Rica. In Brazil, diagnostics of cattle ranching systems indicate that legumes and trees are a pertinent way for emissions reductions and a GIS data base on land use changes is now available.', 'Contributions demonstrate application of new knowledge learned and gender sensitivity in policymaking processes regarding Livestock NAMA in Colombia and Low Emission Livestock Strategy in Costa Rica.'), ('45', '5', '42', '2015', 'In Brazil a GIS analysis quantifying the links between deforestation, land tenure and agricultural intensification suggests that the “Green Municipality” model was effective to reduce deforestation but is limited to promote sustainable and low emissions cattle ranching, so additional incentives are required. Five prospective participatory local workshops with local actors suggest ways forward. And at regional level, LAMNET network is supporting knowledge sharing among countries regarding not only GHG emissions but also low emissions practices through bilateral dialogues and results exchange.', 'Not applicable.'), ('46', '5', '176', '2015', 'The WB published an advisory report for policy makers in Nicaragua, which provides the basis for operationalizing the policy dialogue between the Government of Nicaragua, WB and other development partners and supports the prioritization of government investment and strategies. The report is based on CIAT/CCAFS CSA Country Profile for Nicaragua.In Colombia, departmental government is interested in using Local Adaptation Plans as a strategy to include in the Departmental Development Plan, this engagement has been made based on the eveidence showed in the Los Cerrillos-Cauca CSV. In adittion, future scenarios methodology was useful to formulate Costa Rica INDCs. Based on the success of Local Technical Agroclimatic Committees where CCAFS enabled dialogue between scientists and local actors on agroclimatic information to support farmers decision making process, the government of Colombia included it as an adaptation strategy in Colombia INDCs.', 'In 2015 decision makers contributed to knowledge products on gender integration in climate change policies in the agricultural sector of Nicaragua. Contributions demonstrate application of new knowledge learned and gender sensitivity in policymaking processes.'), ('47', '5', '177', '2015', 'Using the future scenarios methodology Honduras Adaptation Strategy for the Agricultural Sector was streghthen. CCAFS also enabled the dialogue between IFPRI and CIAT scientists and National Government of Colombia in order to support with the combination of land use, partial economic and crop models the formulation of INDCs.', 'Not applicable'), ('48', '5', '178', '2015', 'IFAD increasingly adopts CIAT/CCAFS science in project design and implementation in Nicaragua (Climate change impact assessment on coffee and cocoa supply chains) and countries in other regions such Comoros, Liberia and Uganda. The IFAD/ASAP project using CCAFS/CIAT climate science are worth >100 MIO USD.', 'In 2015 decision makers contributed to knowledge products on gender integration in climate change policies in the agricultural sector. Contributions demonstrate application of new knowledge learned and gender sensitivity in policymaking processes'), ('49', '5', '179', '2015', 'Scenarios work will be done during 2016 in order to support local planning processes in two more countries in the region supporting the regional approach. In Costa Rica, departmental government is interested in the methodology for programs starting this year.', 'Gender balance, as well as the representation of vulnerable groups, was always taken into account in workshop process design.'), ('50', '8', '171', '2015', 'Various CSA technologies, practices and services were identified, prioritized and implemented for testing, evaluation and development of portfolios of climate smart interventions based on agro-ecological zones, crop/cropping systems and farm typology in SA. Climate risks assessment, bio-physical and socio-economic surveys and development of CSA technology pool were also completed in many new CSV locations using CSV framework developed by CCAFS-SA. CCAFS and CIMMYT in collaboration with local partners have developed a data collection protocol for testing and evaluation of CSA technologies in CSV pilot areas. \r\n\r\nCIMMYT has developed criteria and business assessment tool to identify and evaluate business opportunities and barriers for CSA technologies in CSV pilot locations in India. Portfolio of climate smart interventions has been implemented for testing and evaluation in the coastal agricultural system in Bangladesh (WorldFish). Bioversity has started to test drought-tolerant locally adopted varieties in collaboration with ICAR and local farmers in many locations India.', 'Projects have identified CSA technologies and practices that could be relevant for gender and small/marginal farmers and included in the pilot studies in different agro-ecological zones. Prioritization and development of portfolios of climate smart technologies, best practices and services consider feasibility and preferences based on gender and farm typology. Furthermore, gender is one of the impact evaluation criteria for CSA/CSVs.'), ('51', '8', '172', '2015', 'Database for biophysical, socio-economic and tradeoff analyses for climate smart interventions in agriculture have been developed for various CSV locations from a collaborative work among CCAFS, CG centers and local partners. These datasets are used to develop business models for individual and combination of CSA technologies and different type of CSVs. A methodological framework farm typology analysis have been also developed in collaboration with local partners and farmers group to link with CSA interventions in different farming systems.\r\n\r\nIn addition, CIMMYT and State Department of agriculture in Haryana, Bihar and Punjab have developed framework and guidelines including CSVs approach for local adaptation plan of action (LAPA). CCAFS-SA has done CSA prioritization for Bihar state in India and Bangladesh using CSAP toolkit, multi-objective trade-off analysis among food production, emission and income to prepare adaptation plans (state and national levels) for agriculture.', 'Gender segregated data were collected and socio-economic and tradeoff analyses also considers gender and social issues such as potential benefits to women and small/marginal farmers.'), ('52', '8', '173', '2015', 'New CSV pilot projects in the region have used new CSV framework to develop strategies and scaling up/out plan for CSA in different agro-ecological zones. This framework includes a systematic steps of testing and evaluation of CSVs i.e. climatic risks analyses, identification and prioritization of CSA options, evidences generation, development of scaling up/out plans/schemes, and integration in the existing policies and institutions. WorldFish in Bangladesh, ICRISAT in India and National Partners (LI-BIRD and Practical Action) are using this framework to test and evaluate different models of CSVs. \r\n\r\nCG Centers in collaboration with national and local partners have developed some scaling up/out mechanisms for climate risk management in agriculture. CIMMYT has developed incentive framework for multi-actor institutional mechanism for mainstreaming CSA interventions in local adaptation plans. UTFI approach developed by IWMI and being tested in India and Bangladesh can help to capture flood water and groundwater recharge.', 'CIMMYT has developed robust gender-responsive framework for targeting and implementing CSAPs within CSVs for increased adoption. CSV framework developed by CCAFS envisions positive impact on social inclusion for agriculture dependent communities by including women and marginal farmers in the CSV program. Additionally, projects are collecting gender segregated data for further analyses.'), ('53', '8', '174', '2015', 'Local innovation platform for CSA/CSV has been established in Haryana and Bihar (CIMMYT and CCAFS). These platforms bring together different CGIAR Centers, NARS and Private Sector for participator evaluation of diverse CSA technologies in farmers’ field. These planforms also becoming learning sites for many CSA interventions. Many farmers, government sector officials, NGO/INGOs and private sector organizations are frequently visiting these platforms. Bioversity has developed ClimMob 2.0, an online platform for CSA citizen science, which is now available online (www.climmob.net). CCAFS SA team in collaboration with CG centers has strategically engaged with key stakeholders and local partners to provide technical know-how and capacity building in project design, implementation and M&E.', 'Local innovation platform includes selection and implementation of gender friendly climate smart interventions in agriculture and capacity building in climate change adaptation. The online platform for CSA citizen science includes gender-segregated data and put emphasis on the important of participation by both women and men.'), ('54', '8', '46', '2015', 'CCAFS-SA has worked with World Food Program and Ministry of Agriculture in Nepal and CEGIS in Bangladesh to develop new climate datasets for CRAFT tool. These dataset were used for in-season crop yield assessment and climatic risks analysis at sub-national and local level. CSA/CSV project in Nepal has used these dataset for prioritization of CSA options in different agro-ecological locations.', 'Not applicable'), ('55', '8', '47', '2015', 'Technical feasibility analysis of implementing ICT based agro-advisory system in pilot climate smart villages has been done in Nepal. This project has identified the local vendor which disseminates mobile-based agro-advisory services in the CSV sites.', 'Not applicable'), ('56', '8', '48', '2015', 'CCAFS-SA has developed an innovative methodology for developing rainfall triggers with higher satisfaction of farmers, industry and government in collaboration with Agriculture Insurance Company of India and Agriculture Department of Maharashtra for rice, pearl millet, soybean and cotton in Maharashtra state. The Government of Maharashtra has used these improved insurance products to protect one million farmers in 2015 alone. Similarly, a theoretical framework of climate-smart insurance has been developed by IFPRI to design insurance products for the farmers who implement climate smart technologies and practices in particular crop. \r\n\r\nDevelopment of Index-based Flood Insurance (IBFI) products for India (Bihar) and Bangladesh (Sirajganj) has started with engagement and communication with local communities, officials as well as Ministries of Disasters and Agriculture. These agencies are participating in the research and committing in-kind resources to implement IBFI scheme by subsidizing insurance premium for farmers indicating increasing acceptance of the concept and program.', 'Gender dis-aggregated data has been collected to incorporate gender issues in climate smart insurance products. Potential of linking up gender and social inclusion with national programs in flood insurance has been explored. Additionally, the ongoing project on Index-based Flood Insurance (IBFI) has involved women and smallholders to identify potential benefit from the project to them.'), ('57', '8', '49', '2015', 'CCAFS-SA has worked in collaboration with World Food Program-Nepal for in-season crop yield assessment using CRAFT developed by CCAFS. We have raised the capacity of WFP and the Government agencies in using  seasonal crop outlooks. Outputs of this assessment have been used by Nepal Food Security Monitoring System (NeKSAP), Department of Agriculture to produce seasonal crop outlooks for rice and wheat. This has found good acceptance.', 'Not applicable'), ('58', '8', '40', '2015', 'Databases on GHG emission including estimation of emission factor for various management options in wheat and maize-based cropping system in Indo-genetic region (CIMMYT) and pulses in dryland/rainfed (ICRISAT) have been developed. CIMMYT has also developed a database on GHG emission from agriculture and livestock production at national level in India.', 'Not applicable'), ('59', '8', '41', '2015', 'Systematic assessment and review of mitigation related activities in some locations in India provides rich information to identify and prioritize low-emission CSA options. Several options such as change in tillage and crop established methods, use of crop residues, method and time of nutrient application could be help to reduce GHG emission intensity from the crop lands. These datasets are being used as inputs to a CFT-derived tool to develop a unique \'bottom-up\' set of cost-effective mitigation options in India.', 'Not applicable'), ('60', '8', '42', '2015', 'Not available for SA', 'Not available for SA'), ('61', '8', '176', '2015', 'Inventories of policies for CSA in Bangladesh, India, Nepal and Sri Lanka have been prepared by IFPRI. In Bangladesh, IFPRI and CCAFS-Scenario’s studies contributed into the Bangladesh’s 7th Five-Year Plan. CCAFS has been coordinating scenarios for Bangladesh National Adaptation Plan. A decision support tool (CSAP) was used in formulation of national adaptation plan (draft document for Bangladesh). CSA scaling up project in Nepal funded by CDKN has reviewed current policy and institutional framework and CSA initiatives provide inputs to develop scaling up/out plans for Nepal.\r\n\r\nBhutan and Nepal have appointed national organizations to lead the national policy development processes to implement the ITPGRFA. In Bhutan formal regulations or executive orders were developed to officially appoint these organizations. New amendments to existing laws for the implementation of the CBD/NP and the Treaty in a mutually supportive manner was done in Bhutan and Nepal.', 'Generation of gender disaggregated information relevant to improve the planning process were collected. Project activities also include review of current policy and institutional framework and CSA initiatives. These information have provided guidelines to include gender and social issues in scaling up/out plans and programs at national, sub-national and local levels.'), ('62', '8', '177', '2015', 'Several high level engagements and communication meetings with key stakeholders of CSA/CSV have been conducted in India, Bangladesh, Nepal and Bhutan. CCAFS-SA in collaboration with CG centers, national and local partners has organized several capacity building training on priority setting for CSA options, designing portfolios of technologies/practices/services, implementation of CSA/CSV programs at sub-national and local level. Multi-objective trade-off analyses, socio-economic scenario analysis is done for formulating NAPs/SAP in India (Bihar) and Bangladesh. Priority setting was one of the focus task for IFPRI to implement CSA project in Karnataka State of India.', 'Projects in SA have collected and used gender dis-aggregated information for priority setting in agriculture. IFPRI has used its Women’s Empowerment in Agriculture Index (WEAI) to understand gender role and share in decision-making and highlight the gender dimensions in government policies and programs.'), ('63', '8', '178', '2015', 'Not available for SA', 'Not available for SA'), ('64', '8', '179', '2015', 'CCAFS scenario team has actively engaged with policy makers to contextualize South Asia regional scenario analysis in Bangladesh.  The Bangladesh 7th 5 Year Plan was developed using scenarios, focusing on contributions on CCAFS key areas, as well as broader resilience aspects. CCAFS-SA has also contributed into UNFCCC SBSTA and major DFID outcome case from South Asia.', 'Gender balance, as well as the representation of vulnerable groups, was always taken into account in scenario workshop.'), ('65', '9', '171', '2015', 'The CSV teams and the communities conducted the following activities: 1) participatory land-use planning (PLUP-CC), results of which would input in the CSV plans co-designed by stakeholders; and 2) identification of the most suitable CSA Techniques & Practices (T&P). Need-based trainings on farm management and livelihoods were also conducted in Tra Hat, Ekxang and Pailom CSVs. A cross-country learning activity participated by CSV leaders and local partners showcased potential CSA T&Ps  in the Philippines, bringing about the establishment of demonstration sites in 3 CSVs. Access to local weather information in Ma and My Loi CSVs is being enhanced', 'In general, gender and social inclusion is always considered in any activity. For Vietnam and the Philippines, home garden improvement and livestock-raising are the two CSA practices that women showed interest in. The CSA prioritization activities at the CSV level were analyzed though gender lens, carefully considering gender differentiation and concerns of marginalized farmers and other relevant sectors. In some CSVs, at least 5 active female farmers have been identified to lead groups for testing activities; about 5-7 households have been selected to test the prioritized CSA T&Ps and receive additional support from the project in implementing the tests'), ('66', '9', '172', '2015', 'The following tools and methods were assessed: 1) Used of guidelines for Participatory Land Use Planning adopted for CC and  calibration of a land use optimization tool, at farm level; 2) application of a framework for CSA prioritization setting,  and a cost-benefit analysis (CBA)  for identifying suitable CSA for testing in the CSVs; 3) Trade-off analysis for AWD in Tra Hat 4)  Testing of future scenarios of aquaculture in the Mekong River Delta; 5) Use of LIDAR model  to simulate future impacts of storm surges to agriculture and livelihood; and  6) Developing the concept and framework on local governance for the proof-of-concept sites', 'Gender and social dimensions in the decision-support tools and guidelines (i.e., PLUP-CC and CSA prioritization) were explicitly considered in their application. In particular, the CBA work was modified to include poor/disadvantaged households. The CSA prioritization exercise in Ma and My Loi CSVs engaged women and disadvantaged farmers'), ('67', '9', '173', '2015', 'Two up-scaling approaches are being tested in SEA. One approach that is being done on a national scale focuses on catalyzing roll-out of CSA adoption across Vietnam. This includes preliminary activities like information profiling and stakeholder analysis with mapping of key actors and their influences toward development outcomes. Another approach attempts to generate evidences in 8 (Philippines: 6 and Vietnam: 2) impact areas consisting of 15 villages. An impact area is defined as contiguous sites with observable evidences of co-benefits of CSA and CBA and community-of-practice of CSA exist and actively involve farmer-centered extension through common-interest groups.', 'Both up-scaling approaches have consistently addressed gender dimensions. The information profiling and stakeholder mapping involved women stakeholders. While the IIRR- and ICRAF-led project was able to identify two key CSA practices, home garden improvement and livestock-raising, as most relevant to women. Women participation is also high in community level activities (e.g., trainings, workshops, field days, media day and demonstrations).'), ('68', '9', '174', '2015', 'The following knowledge management activities were resulted in: 1) PLUP-CC trainings among CSV teams improved their capacities in developing local CC adaptation plans; 2) The cross-country learning allowed CSV leaders gain firsthand knowledge of different CSA options. 3) Multi-stakeholder learning platforms (e.g., meetings, field visits) in the CSVs helped define roles and established collective action. 4) Information campaigns (i.e., informediaries, forum, workshops, field days, competitions) complemented with information products increased the awareness and appreciation of the CSA approach of thousands farmers, students and village development planners', 'To ensure gender and social inclusion, careful consideration was into securing active participation of women across regional activities. Learning platforms (i.e., PLUP-CC process, special trainings in Phailom CSV, and meetings on mobile app) always involved women.  The CSA prioritization exercises in Ma and My Loi CSVs engaged women and disadvantaged farmers, likewise, in extension services for the home and school gardening projects. A gender study by IRRI documented and analyzed women’s roles in rice-based farming in Vietnam.  Champion female farmers will be identified to lead testing groups and disseminate knowledge/experience in testing CSA options'), ('69', '9', '175', '2015', 'Rice farmers in Tra Hat and Phailom CSVs have improved their knowledge on sustainable production techniques in rice cultivation through the projects on \"SRP Standard for Sustainable Rice Cultivation\" and \"Greenhouse Gas Emissions\" for catalyzing roll-out of adoption', 'Gender aspects have consistently been addressed as a cross-cutting issue in the region through significant representation in training courses and conducting gender studies. In the IRRI project on “Standard for Sustainable Rice Cultivation”, \"women empowerment\" is one of performance indicators, reinforcing the intent to integrate gender parity in research initiatives'), ('70', '9', '46', '2015', 'IRRI pre-tested a beta version of climate-informed, ICT-based, agro advisory services for the Mekong Delta and Red River Delta. This version recorded farmers’ demographic characteristics which can be used for better matching of farming advice and specific services needed by households and farmers.  Meanwhile, ICRAF identified climate-yield impacts using available statistical data, and started mentorship between national and provincial meteorological officers on improving weather forecast.  The project advisory group in Ha Tinh and Dien Bien was also organized for out-scaling of project results. Risk maps for climate-sensitive zoonotic diseases using the 40-year climate data is currently being developed by ILRI', 'To better match the agro-advisory service with the varying needs of men and women farmers, IRRI ensured that at least 20% of participants in the pilot testing of the agro-advisory services in 2015 were women farmers.  With this in consideration, it is expected that national and local partners will be motivated to utilize agro-advisory services appropriately by considering gender and other marginalized groups. On the other hand, results of the baseline survey conducted by ICRAF and CARE highlighted aspects where gender-differentiated agro-climate information interventions are more and less relevant.'), ('71', '9', '47', '2015', 'The CCAFS projects have initiated the development of new knowledge and tools to support equitable climate services for farmers. ICRAF and CARE have developed and piloted the agro-climatic handbook and methods for downscaled agro-climate zone maps. To ensure that research, policy and capacity gaps is addressed in developing and testing farmer-relevant, locally appropriate and equitable agro-climatic services, a baseline study was conducted in the project sites. ILRI has initiated a pioneering study which investigates the seasonality of climate-sensitive diseases in Vietnam. This initiative would be useful in developing policies for public health, agriculture and environment vis-a-vis livestock improvement.', 'In the baseline study conducted in Dien Bien and Ha Tinh provinces in Vietnam, ICRAF obtained information on men and women farmers’ needs and use of agro-climate information and preferred formats and contents. Survey results would provide further insights on the capacity needs to empower women farmers. Although the ILRI project does not have a strong gender component yet, there are plans to conduct a survey on farmers’ awareness of climate-sensitive diseases. Results of the planned survey are expected to provide insights to the differences of farmers’ awareness levels based on demographic characteristics, with focus on gender'), ('72', '9', '48', '2015', 'The projects under this flagship do not have any contributions towards this specific MOG.', 'The projects under this flagship do not have any contributions towards this specific MOG.'), ('73', '9', '49', '2015', 'With the goal of contributing to the development of decision support systems in Vietnam, ILRI conducted a systematic literature review to understand the relationship between CC and zoonotic diseases. Monthly data on diseases like viral encephalitis and leptospirosis, along with the weather data of the province for the last 20 years were obtained for analysis. Although it is known that the occurrence of zoonotic diseases is strongly influenced by CC, little is known about their epidemiology in Vietnam and Laos. ILRI in collaboration with its national partners has planned to collect samples across Vietnam to further understand these diseases', 'The project started in the middle of July 2015 and focus was mainly on a systematic literature review. No gender component was considered over the last reporting period'), ('74', '9', '50', '2015', 'Studies at the national level were conducted by ILRI to evaluate the sero-prevalence of climate-sensitive diseases. The findings of this evaluation opened the opportunity to understand the epidemiology of diseases as well as to identify the potential environmental and climate risk factors associated with this. National data on human disease cases and climate data were also obtained to develop evidence and knowledge products. ILRI has implemented the epidemiological data and prepared communication materials, such as posters, leaflets and news articles for publication to increase awareness on climate-sensitive diseases at the national level', 'The projects under the Flagship 2 do not have any gender components relating to this MOG.'), ('75', '9', '40', '2015', 'A low-cost measurement method for quantifying GHGs (SAMPLES) was made available online. A database for Tier-2 emission factors measured by CCAFS and partners was created and disseminated. A training on measuring GHG emissions from agriculture was provided to 8 PhD scientists from developing countries (CLIFF Network).\r\n\r\nILRI developed a GIS database on the drivers and initial values for simulating rice production at the national scale for Vietnam. Using a process-oriented modeling linked to GIS databases, the first national inventory of CH4 emissions from rice paddies have been developed.  WorldFish has also started assessing the potential of aquaculture as sources of GHGs', 'Female staffs of the Institute of Agricultural Environment (Vietnam) were trained on the tools and techniques for calculating GHG emission inventories (national scale). These female scientists will eventually do the GHGs emission measurement for national reporting of GHG emissions and this is a step toward increasing their capacity and skills in doing so. The training will enable partners like IAE and MARD to improve the Mitigation Plan at the national level (MARD’s 20-20-20) as well as the regional level (MRD and Central Vietnam). Of the 8 scientists (CLIFF) trained, 6 were women'), ('76', '9', '41', '2015', 'The following applications of support tools were done: 1)development of aspirational mitigation target for agriculture to meet 2-degree target including analysis of Vietnam’s agriculture mitigation scenario for their INDCs; 2)Identification of CH4 emissions hotspots in rice systems in Vietnam, providing baseline data for the CH4 reduction target; 3)Analysis of stakeholder using NetMap in several Vietnamese provinces to know the prevailing power structure and influences, information flow, and relationships among stakeholders who control the landscape and/or policy formulation and implementation  that was conducted separately by IFPRI and IRRI; 4)Initiation of in-depth activity monitoring of the local regulation on peat  by CIFOR', 'In this particular MOG, gender roles in the mitigation and adaptation plans are included in Vietnam’s INDC. Women representation was ensured in IRRI’s NetMap activity, though, gender and social inclusion were not much tackled in the same activity conducted by IFPRI.  The CIFOR-led project gave priority on social inclusion during the monitoring activity of the local regulation on peat with lots of attention paid to village management plans. ILRI involved women in their training'), ('77', '9', '42', '2015', 'The agronomic and economic incentives for farmers to adopt AWD are being analyzed by IRRI. In coordination with the associated CCAC project, farmers\' perceptions are being analyzed and new dissemination strategies are being developed.  Reviews of economics of AWD in paddy rice, balanced N fertilizer use, and monitoring, reporting and verification was also done.  CIFOR conducted in-depth monitoring activities of the local regulation on peat but the project was terminated, hence, results could not be properly shared and discussed with relevant actors', 'The CIFOR project works on the principle of social inclusion during the monitoring activity of the local regulation on peat, hence, no specific gender aspect is indicated. In the IRRI project, a gender study was conducted which gave detailed recommendations for each project activity. Women participated in the field experiments under this study'), ('78', '9', '176', '2015', 'CCAFS supported and participated in multi-stakeholder consultation workshops providing inputs into national (Vietnam, Myanmar, Cambodia, Philippines) and regional plans (ASEAN CRN) on CC. IRRI provided inputs to Vietnam’s rice sector restructuring. It has also initiated several activities to better understand the policy formulation mechanism and implementation process in target countries. IFPRI organized a science-policy dialogue in the Philippines, where studies on modeling scenarios and outputs were presented and deliberated. High-level policymakers from government, NGOs, international research organizations, and other key stakeholders participated in the forum. In Cambodia, CCAFS scenarios were used to guide and initiate two new policy processes focused on business', 'CCAFS SEA ensured that gender dimensions and marginalized groups are considered and included in the development of national climate resiliency and food security plans and programs. Understanding gender issues have been appropriately addressed through the conduct of a case study and a research on gender differences in CC perception, vulnerability and adaptation strategies and technologies (IFPRI) and these were presented in a policy forum and will be published in a forthcoming book. Case studies on gender differences in CC perception and adaptation strategies were conducted by PIRCCA in Vietnam and Myanmar. The Vietnam case study has been published online'), ('79', '9', '177', '2015', 'IRRI conducted a follow-up inquiry in Vietnam on the information needs of national-level stakeholders’ decision-making in addressing CC challenges. Respondents were asked on their experiences on CC policymaking and knowledge on CSA technologies to better recognize information needs for policy formulation and identify analysis tools significant for decision-making. Meanwhile, IFPRI developed modeling outputs and innovative scenario assessments to establish decision-support mechanisms on agriculture, CC and food security policies in the Philippines. These outputs were presented in a policy forum/dialogue with audience consisting of high-level policymakers from the government, NGOs, international/national research organizations, and other key stakeholders', 'Research study and case studies that establish the socio-economic context and scenario of gender issues for Vietnam, Myanmar (by PIRCCA) and the Philippines (by IFPRI) have been conducted. Reports for Vietnam and the Philippines have been published online and the Myanmar report is underway. Adaptation and mitigation plans that consider gender differentiations can build on these studies, and gaps and areas where interventions are most needed can be determined'), ('80', '9', '178', '2015', 'A regional workshop on CSA technologies in Asia was sponsored by UNEP and organized by PIRCCA. Participants from 13 Asian countries attended the 2-day workshop, along with several international and regional (ASEAN CRN)/national stakeholders. The workshop consisted of presentations on technical, organizational, and financial aspects of CSA technologies and a field visit to IRRI to view the development and testing of CSA technologies. This enabled the broader awareness of and increased support to the CSA approach in the level of supra-national governance systems. As an output, participating countries are drafting concept notes to be submitted for funding from the AP-CTNFC', 'PIRCCA’s study on the gender differences in CC perception, access to climate information and adaptation and coping strategies in the three provinces in Vietnam’s MRD did not provide any strong evidence that gender gap exists in any of these areas. The study also indicated that impacts of CC in Vietnam do not appear to be individual but rather disaggregated at the household level or more likely at the landscape level. It is recommended that future gender research in Vietnam should focus on adaptation and coping strategies during CC stress as it appears that gender differences are present in this aspect.'), ('81', '9', '179', '2015', 'The scenarios work led by Oxford University resulted in the following: 1) WWF used CCAFS-SEA scenarios recommendations for ADB document “Investment in Natural Capital for Sustainable Future in GMS; 2) the Cambodian government with support from CCAFS is using the scenarios approach for a project on ASEAN CSR; and 3) in partnership with Oxfam Asia, a scenario process on climate adaptation was organized in the Philippines.', 'Gender balance and the involvement of vulnerable groups were considered in the workshop design'), ('82', '1', '171', '2015', 'Guided by on location specific climatic risks and stakeholders priorities (and based on agro-ecological zones, crop/cropping systems and farm typology in the case of India), several context specific suitable crop, livestock and water storage CSA technologies and practices were identified, prioritized and implemented in CSVs across all regions for evaluation and development of portfolios through PAR. Those included:\r\n\r\n• Drought and mosaic-tolerant cassava, drought-tolerant maize; drought and rust-tolerant common bean and low moisture-tolerant pigeon pea, fast-growing and tolerant to worms galla goats and red-Masaai sheep, Bracharia, Sweet potato vines (EA); drought-tolerant beans and forages (LAM), drought tolerant wheat and beans (SA); \r\n• Soil fertility and grain storage management (EA), crop rotation, water storage options, water conservation techniques (tied-ridging, bunding, zai), conservation agriculture, agroforestry and tree-shaded coffee/cocoa (WA); in LAM and SEA CSVs 14 relevant existing CSA technologies/strategies identified to increase farmers adaptive capacities (incl. diversification, home gardening, drip irrigation, water harvesting livestock raising, intercropping, forestry, agroforestry, soil improvement, water harvest & management, weather forecast, coastal bioshields, community seed bank, coffee rejuvenation).\r\n• Testing Future scenarios of aquaculture in Mekong\'s Delta \r\n• Evidence for the productive profitable, adapted and scalable CSAPs was quantified in India (~50 CSV in Haryana & Bihar).', 'Several CSA prioritization activities at the CSV level and On-farm/on-station field evaluations were designed and analyzed though gender lens, and ensured gender and social inclusion through:\r\n\r\n• Identificating best-bet CSA options that are relevant/specific for gender and small/marginal farmers and consideration of feasibility, preferences and differential impacts (e.g priority tree species in EA; home garden improvement and livestock-raising in SEA and EA; non timber forest product processing -baobab fruit transformation and Casia tora growing in WA)\r\n• Implementing participatory mechanisms to account for gender perspective and framing culturally-appropriate and gender equitable approaches (LAM)\r\n• Fostering women’s group participation/leadership in evaluation trials (Kenyan CBOs consisting of 60% women; SEA), \r\n• Collecting gender disaggregated data (SA, EA, LAM)'), ('83', '1', '172', '2015', 'Methodologies for local adaptation planning and CSA prioritization tools developed or applied included: \r\n\r\n• Farm typology analysis framework (EA, SA)\r\n• LIDAR model simulating future impacts of storm surges (SEA)\r\n• Future seed zonation maps, shade tree advise tool and tree fodder nutrition database for feeds/forages priority setting (EA, LAM)\r\n• Atlas for fruit/shade species prioritization in agroforestry coffee systems (LAM) and Climate-smart planning framework (WA) \r\n• AgMIP integrated assessments for CSA prioritization (EA)\r\n• Bayesian-networks algorithms for CSA targeting developed and piloted with Tanzania MoA and ACSAA\r\n• USAID CSA indicator/programing tool\r\n• Prioritization framework and cost-benefit analysis for CSA investment (LAM, WA, SEA); CSAP toolkit and multi-objective trade-off analysis for state/national levels adaptation plans (India and Bangladesh);  climate-smartness analysis of Farmer-Managed Natural-Tree-Regeneration (Niger); Ongoing socio-economical trade-off analysis in coffee regions (Uganda), of AWD (SEA) and data collection (WA, SA) \r\n• Evidence published for LAPA&CSVs synergies as climate change adaptation strategy(SA)\r\n• Farm-level land use optimization tool (SEA)\r\n• Draft LAPA developed for Nyando. \r\n• Framework and Guidelines on participatory Local-Adaptation-Planning developed in India and Colombia\r\n• Concept and framework developed on local governance for the proof-of-concept sites SEA\r\n• Innovative data collection/analysis approaches developed in LAM (citizen science)', '•GSI dimensions considered in targeting,prioritization planning tools and NEPAD practical guide (i.e., PLUP-CC in SEA, CSA framework in WA, LAM, SA, SEA); Women engaged and beneficiaries of the process; Mali’s portfolio included income diversification option with fish ponds targeted to women;in Senegal gender dimension addressed in the extensive pastoralist systems.\r\n•Framework being developed to plan for gender-specific interventions in climate-smart coffee/cocoa systems.\r\n•Gender considered in: Weighted means and Bayesian networks targeting methods; AGMIP analyses; the shade tree advice tool. \r\n•Gender-disaggregated data collection in Rural Household Multiple Indicator Survey (Citizen Science) and inclusion of indicator on gender-specific control of livelihood activities/income streams.\r\n•Gender segregated data collection and socio-economic and tradeoff analyses that considers potential benefits of CSA options to women and small/marginal farmers (EA,SA).\r\n•CBA work was modified in SEA to include poor/disadvantaged households\r\n•Youth and women in Nyando will be involved in validation of draft local adaptation plan.'), ('84', '1', '173', '2015', '•The USAID-FTFportfolio was analyzed globally for CSA-opportunities and entry-points.\r\n• A CSV framework used across all regions to develop strategies and scaling up/out plans.Regional specificities include:\r\n\r\nIn SA:New framework including systematic steps for testing/evaluating different CSV models (from climatic risks analyses to integration in existing policies/institutions) being used (WorldFish in Bangladesh, ICRISAT in India, LI-BIRD and Practical Action). UTFI approach is being tested in India and Bangladesh to capture flood water and groundwater recharge (IWMI). Incentive framework for mainstreaming CSA interventions in local adaptation plans developed (CIMMYT/partners).\r\n \r\nIn SEA:Two up-scaling approaches tested: One at national-scale focused on catalyzing roll-out of CSA adoption (Vietnam), another attempting to generate evidences in impact areas (Vietnam and Philippines).\r\n\r\nIn EA:AIP established aiming at enhancing the role of agri-business in scaling CSA (Kenya). \r\n\r\nIn WA:Development of business cases to support scaling out of water storage options. Scaling pathways identified via public policy and private companies in Ghana. \r\n\r\nSystems framework was developed to plan for climate smart coffee/cocoa sector (EA, WA) and networks are being developed in Peru with coffee and cocoa producer exporter organizations, NGOs and public sector to strenghten engagement and further scaling up.\r\n\r\nIn LAM: Participatory local adaptation planning is being scaled-out by local partner (Northern Colombia) and discussions with UNEP and FAO are ongoing for scaling.Results from the CSA prioritization framework were used in Guatemala as strategy to scale out the methodology through the national extension service.', '•CSV framework developed envisions positive impact on social inclusion for agriculture dependent communities by including women and marginal farmers (SA). \r\n•Framework on mainstreaming gender for scaling CSA.\r\n•SEA’s up-scaling approaches have consistently addressed gender dimensions and the information profiling and stakeholder mapping involved women stakeholders. \r\n•Gender inclusive AIP established in Kenya.\r\n•In WA: Gender focused projects implemented on: understanding male and female farmers’ access and use of climate information (Ghana); valorizing non-timber forest products and assessing the performance of Cassia tora and cowpea under improved zai techniques for increased resilience (Niger). \r\n•Role of gender identified as key in the selection and use of different water storage options supporting women and youth for business case development.'), ('85', '1', '174', '2015', '•High level workshop held with 10 major agencies to develop a common overall CSA metrics framework. \r\n•Networking and CCAFS products dissemination at the London Resilient Supply Chains Conference\r\n•P4S-CSA project positionned as key knowledge broker in the CSA discussion. The African Perspective on CSA; Inputs integrated into NEPAD Practical guide and GACSA \'s Knowledge Action Group.\r\n\r\n•Global learning CSV workshop to reflect on lessons learnt, methodological harmonization and cross-regional analyses.\r\n•Policy level engagements on climate literacy.\r\n•CSVs in SA, WA and EA working as effective local innovation platforms (Haryana and Bihar\'s focused on LAPAs) and becoming learning-sites.\r\n \r\n•New multi-stakeholder learning platforms established to support collective action, cross-country learning (SEA) and coffee/cocoa value chains (LAM,WA).  \r\n•Methodology to identify/prioritize capacity-building needs(WA)\r\n•Policy level engagements on climate literacy(SA)\r\n•Training/empowerment of local stakeholders/technicians/producers associations on:\r\n\r\n-CSA, prioritization framework and agroforestry(Mali, Ghana, Vietnam) \r\n-Adaptation planning, CSA testing/implementation(SEA, LAM, WA). \r\n-ICTs and the Site-specific-Agriculture platform for efficient data collection/analysis and strengthening cooperatives’ internal control systems (LAM).\r\n-Local rural radios and mobile apps for project planning/evaluation (WA) and crop management recommendation (SEA); participatory sms content development programme rolled-out in Tanzania. \r\n\r\n•Updated Climate Wizard (outputs integrated into CSA National Framework Programs in five African Countries).\r\n•Draft version of interactive web mapping tool to support the Africa CSA Alliance planning efforts (http://nkoech.github.io/africacsa/).\r\n•Online platform for CSA citizen science (www.climmob.net). \r\n•Global Yield Gap Atlas\r\n\r\nInformation campaigns complemented with information products (policy briefs, manuals) increased the awareness and appreciation of the CSA approach of thousands farmers, students and village development planners', 'Gender and CC Network established to promote collaborative research, sharing of methods and approaches; exchange experience on project design and implementation among CGIAR researchers. \r\n\r\nLearning event: Closing the Gender Gap in Climate Change held in Paris.\r\n\r\n•Local innovation platforms in CSVs include selection and implementation of gender sensitive climate-smart interventions and participation of women’s groups (home gardening and school gardening) and poor/disadvantaged farmers in testing. \r\n\r\n•Women and youth’s higher affinity and skills to use ICTs for accessing information highlighted by CSMS project results (LAM)\r\n\r\n•Active participation of women secured across knowledge sharing and trainings activities (WA, EA, SA, SEA, LAM) \r\n\r\n•Champion female farmers will be leading testing groups and disseminating knowledge/experience in SEA.\r\n\r\n•The online platform for CSA citizen science includes gender-segregated data and emphasizes the important of participation by both women and men (SA,LAM,EA).\r\n\r\n•PRODECOOP monitoring systems included CSA gender-specific and gender-related indicators in coffee landscapes of Nicaragua'), ('86', '1', '175', '2015', '•Discussions advanced with World Bank to trial novel CSA financial options/mechanisms with CARE. \r\n•2 CCAFS projects pitched to the GACSA Investment Action Group \r\n•Active engagement and climate change information provided to NGOs, public and private sector actors involved in coffee and cocoa value chains in WA and LAM is helping to frame the conversation about what needs to be done in 2016 to develop CSA certification schemes. \r\n•Development of National CSA Framework Programs for scaling CSA within 5 African countries (Kenya,Tanzania, Uganda, Botswana and Namibia) by P4S-CSA is providing a basis for developing large funding proposals (e.g. GCF), integration into INDCs and sub-national implementation plans. \r\n•AIP established in Kenya aiming at enhancing the role of agri-business in scaling CSA. \r\n•Criteria and a business assessment tool developed to identify and evaluate business cases opportunities/ barriers from CSA perspective. \r\n•Primary and secondary data collected in India for developing business models including bio-physical, socio-economic and trade-off analyses; Documentation of CSA led business cases developed is providing excellent evidence base for attracting rural youth and will help scaling.\r\n•Action plans developed for promising CSA portfolios in Haryana, Bihar and Punjab, India.\r\n•Synthesis report produced on local level incentives & policies supporting CSA for all CSV sites in India.\r\n•Knowledge sharing publication is being developed in LAM on existing climate-smart investment plans from Nicaragua and Guatemala’s small coffee farmers’ cooperatives.', '*Strong gender and social inclusion angle planned for Pilot on financial instruments to be trialed with WB and CARE in 2016 \r\n* NUI’s work focused on reaching smallholder women farmers thorough understanding gender issues in bean value chains and seed systems.\r\n* Gender analysis on coffee/cocoa climate-smart value chains in WA and LAM initiated with a focus on youth and land inheritance.\r\n*ICRAF/CIAT worked with researchers Royal Galloway University to develop CSA gender indicators for use in the CSA Profiles being developed for six African countries and in the CCAFS CSA Prioritization Framework.\r\n*Gender aspects addressed in the business models identification in Africa and Asia'), ('87', '4', '176', '2015', 'CSA Framework Programs were developed in five African countries through CGIAR technical support, which also supported preparation of the Kenyan INDC. Scenario-guided policy processes assisted Tanzania’s Socio-Economic Development plan. The WB published a report for policy makers in Nicaragua to support the prioritization of government investment and strategies, based on the CIAT/CCAFS CSA Country Profile. Scenarios science was used in formulating Costa Rica’s INDC. CCAFS-enabled science-policy dialogue led to the inclusion of agro-climatic information as an adaptation strategy in Colombia’s INDC. IFPRI and CCAFS scenarios science contributed to Bangladesh’s 7th Five-Year Plan and (with the CSAP) tool to the National Adaptation Plan. Bhutan and Nepal have appointed national organizations to lead the national policy development processes to implement the ITPGRFA, as well as amending existing laws for its implementation. CCAFS supported and participated in multi-stakeholder consultation workshops providing inputs into national (Vietnam, Myanmar, Cambodia, Philippines) and regional plans (ASEAN CRN) on climate change. IRRI provided inputs to Vietnam’s rice sector restructuring. IFPRI organized a science-policy dialogue in the Philippines around impacts modelling research outputs.  In Cambodia, CCAFS scenarios were used to initiate two new policy processes focused on business. ECOWAS and member-countries are now effectively mainstreaming CSA into regional and national agricultural plans and policies through the CSA alliance (WACSAA) and implementation framework.  CCAFS made scientific inputs into country action plans and identification of priorities in Ghana, Burkina Faso, and Mali.  Analysis of INDCs has been disseminated within the WB to assist in designing appropriate country strategies and project operations.', 'Reviews of current CSA policy and institutional frameworks were carried out in relation to gender (EA, LAM). IFPRI research on gender differences in CC perception, vulnerability and adaptation in SEA is being published as a book. Similar research was done by PIRCCA in Vietnam and Myanmar. Use of climate information by different groups was monitored in WA; CSA action plans in Ghana are directly involving women. Different perspectives concerning ITPGRFA/MLS were identified and the degree of involvement of women in national policy processes assessed. Effective policy implementation guidelines were developed based on a gender analysis of crop diversification programs in SEA. GSI policy briefs were produced, and gender/youth elements included in the Guide to UNFCCC Negotiations on Agriculture Toolkit. Gender analysis of INDCs was carried out for COP21. Youth from CSVs in EA participated in the Youth Conference on CBA9 and presented the outcome statement at COP 21.'), ('88', '4', '177', '2015', 'A rapid multi-indicator survey tool was developed and applied in four contrasting systems of EA, to assist in incorporating climate change into district development plans. Scenarios methodology was developed and used to strengthen the Honduras Adaptation Strategy for the Agricultural Sector. CCAFS-enabled dialogue around IFPRI-CIAT modelling results with the Colombian Government contributed several priorities to the INDC. Priorities for investment in CSVs were identified using a range of tools in India, Bangladesh, Nepal and Bhutan. Several CGIAR centres and other partners carried out capacity building activities on priority setting for CSA at sub-national and local levels in SA. Multi-objective trade-off and socio-economic scenario analyses were developed and used to formulate adaptation plans in India (Bihar) and Bangladesh. IRRI conducted an information needs assessment of national-level stakeholders’ decision-making in addressing CC challenges, to identify appropriate tools for decision-making. IFPRI’s modelling tools generated research outputs that were used to establish decision-support mechanisms related to CC and food security policies in the Philippines. Scenarios research in Burkina Faso was used to help formulate the PNSR.  In Ethiopia, three national workshops were held to inform policy implementation around CSA, using quantified regional scenarios; this research will be used to identify national investment priorities. Engagement with national meteorological services in Tanzania, Malawi and Ghana around novel data analysis tools is improving their planning processes. Priority setting reviews of adaptation options in mixed crop-livestock systems were carried out; that these are still substantially under-researched was echoed in the INDCs of some countries.', 'In EA, new methods were developed around zonal and systems approaches, to integrate gender equity considerations within rapid multi-indicator surveys. Applications are envisaged at multiple sites to produce a global analysis of the interplay between agriculture, gender and nutrition. Projects in SA collected gender disaggregated information for priority setting. IFPRI used the Women’s Empowerment in Agriculture Index to understand gender roles in decision-making and highlight gender dimensions in government policies and programs. Case studies on gender have been carried out in Vietnam, Myanmar (by PIRCCA) and the Philippines (by IFPRI), with the aim of identifying areas where interventions are most needed. In WA, women were well represented in the nine districts in which scenarios work was carried out. In Tanzania, Malawi and Ghana, women were included specifically in PICSA farmer training.  Syntheses of baselines work in WA and EA are highlighting several key GSI elements in these CCAFS sites.'), ('89', '4', '178', '2015', 'The post-2015 UNFCCC agreement, announced in Paris in December 2015, established a sound international governance framework for climate action. It has an explicit focus on food security, ensuring that agriculture is a sector for action. CCAFS made several written contributions to SBSTA processes. Documented RBM is starting to inform institutional change processes in several organizations. CCAFS science contributed to three submissions (on early warning systems, risks and vulnerability in agricultural systems, and gender and climate change) made by the African Group of Negotiators to UNFCCC discussions. IFAD is adopting CIAT/CCAFS science in project design and implementation in several countries (Nicaragua, Comoros, Liberia, Uganda). IFAD/ASAP projects worth >USD 100 million are using CCAFS/CIAT climate science.  A regional workshop on CSA (UNEP, PIRCCA) included participants from 13 Asian countries and regional (ASEAN CRN) stakeholders; concept notes are being drafted for funding from the AP-CTNFC.  CCAFS helped to set up and support a WA CSA alliance and intervention framework, assisting AUC and NEPAD in developing a technical guide and roadmap for informing NAIPs to achieve the CAADP goals. PICSA interacted with WFP, ADRA, Oxfam and CARE, using their science and tools to bring the climate services needs of smallholder farmers more to the fore. FAO Council adopted CGRFA guidelines in 2015, designed to assist 189 country members in climate change adaptation planning. Reviews were undertaken of which governance arrangements may positively influence food system dynamics and increase food security, the discourses surrounding CSA, and the major governance issues associated with transformations.', 'CCAFS research helped support AGN and civil society groups to prepare submissions on gender and climate change to SBSTA. The CGRFA guidelines provide examples of how national programs can encourage socially marginalized groups to take advantage of the ITPGRFA for CC adaptation. Decision makers in LAM contributed to knowledge products on gender integration in climate change policies in the agricultural sector, increasing gender sensitivity in policymaking processes. In SEA, PIRCCA research is helping to prioritize future gender intervention points. The CCSL is continuing to gather evidence about the efficacy of social learning approaches, revolving around gender-inclusive engagement and learning in research programs to improve development outcomes. Gender received attention in about 40% of the INDCs submitted ahead of COP21. A policy brief on supporting women farmers in a changing climate was developed and disseminated in the lead up to COP21 and informed the updated guide to the negotiations on agriculture.'), ('90', '4', '179', '2015', 'CCAFS continued to engage with the major global players investing in agriculture, including the public sector (World Bank, IFAD, FAO) and the private sector (World Business Council for Sustainable Development). The investment choices of these agencies are likely to become clear in 2016.  CCAFS science has contributed to UNEP’s GEO6 report. Several scientific contributions were made to “CSA 101”, a World Bank e-course for projects and planners. Regarding CCAFS scenarios (led by Oxford University), research was implemented by UNU for ECOWAS on strategies for agriculture and food security planning under climate change. CCAFS collaborated with policy makers on contextualizing the SA regional scenarios in different countries. WWF used CCAFS’s SEA scenarios for an ADB investment document. The Cambodian government was supported by CCAFS to use scenarios methodologies for a project in the ASEAN CSR network.  With Oxfam Asia, a scenarios process on climate adaptation was developed for the Philippines. Future scenarios for the Pacific region were developed by CCAFS and many partners, and these are being built on to guide investments in the region through SPC. IFPRI and partner CGIAR Centres have been improving the IMPACT partial equilibrium model, and the results of model runs have enhanced understanding of the impacts of climate change on food security and informed policy and investment discussions within OECD and FAO. An ICRAF tool has been developed for priority setting and large-scale decision-making across SSA.  The linking of global foresight work with more localised evaluations of different interventions remains work in progress.', 'During the many Oxford University / CCAFS scenario workshops held during 2015, gender balances were monitored, along with the representation of vulnerable groups, in designing and running workshop processes to ensure appropriate participation. IFPRI with a range of partners is carrying out research to link results from the IMPACT partial equilibrium model of the agricultural sector to CGE models. This will provide insights into labour markets, disaggregated by gender, adding an important gender dimension to model (and scenario) outputs. Ongoing research on developing a decision support tool for the World Bank and other investors has an explicit focus on gender and social inclusion. A policy brief on supporting women farmers in a changing climate was developed and widely disseminated in the lead up to COP21 and informed the updated guide to the negotiations on agriculture'), ('91', '3', '40', '2015', 'In 2015 CCAFS scientists generated Tier II and III-level data for smallholder farm emissions in at least nine countries for at least six types of farming systems. Emissions data were collected for improved and degraded pastures in six countries of Latin America (CIAT); and for wheat and maize management interventions in the IGP (CIMMYT) and pulses in dryland/rainfed India (ICRISAT). Collection was started for feed and manure interventions in Kenya (ILRI), but trials were interrupted due to disease outbreak and subsequent killing of animals).  Livestock Plus established infrastructure and methods for measuring livestock emissions in Costa Rica and Colombia (CIAT).  \r\n\r\nInnovations for reducing costs were tested:  In Kenya, a national targeting and county-level sampling strategy were developed (CIFOR).  In Vietnam, a national inventory of methane from rice production was conducted using a process-based model linked to GIS data (ILRI).  EX-ACT analysis of 40 USAID food security projects showed where LED opportunities existed.   In Mongolia, MRV for livestock was developed using M&E that meets stakeholders’ other information needs.\r\n\r\nOther notable achievements include: publishing of the SAMPLES website, including methods for low-cost measurement and a database synthesizing Tier 2 emissions for smallholder farming (cross-center initiative with F3,  7,214 unique users, 13,265 page views);  a dataset of emissions from farming systems in the tropics based on 600 published articles (F3 with ICRAF);  a dataset and statistical analysis of field N2O emissions for the tropics and sub-tropics (CIMMYT),  and training of 8 CLIFF students (F3 with CIAT) and 6 LAMNET students  (CIAT).', 'Gender impacts for this MOG focus on capacity building of women scientists.  In 2015, 6 of the 8 CLIFF students were women. Three women were trained from the IAE in Vietnam in assessing GHGs for national inventories.'), ('92', '3', '41', '2015', 'CCAFS scientists enhanced support for LED decisions in 2015 by identifying impacts of LED practices, prioritizing interventions, setting mitigation goals, identifying mitigation options and providing data for analyzing trade-offs.  \r\n\r\nAssessment of evidence for climate smart practices in dairy (fodder production, feeding practices, animal health and breeding) in Kenya,  livestock in Colombia and Brazil, and conservation agriculture in India provide decision makers with practices relevant to specific agroecosystems.     \r\n\r\nIdentification of emissions hot spots in Vietnam and development of a sampling strategy for interventions related to the Kenya Dairy NAMA provided decision makers information to prioritize interventions.   \r\n\r\nDevelopment of the aspirational mitigation 2-degree target for agriculture globally and for selected countries and analysis of mitigation in INDCs developed for COP21, showing 103 countries pledging mitigation in agriculture, help to guide ambition and mark progress. \r\n\r\nOther supporting analyses for development of NAMAs and LED policy include analysis of 40 USAID projects to identify LED priorities, finance mechanisms in the dairy sector in Kenya;  analysis of dissemination platforms for AWD and stakeholder influence in Vietnam; and analysis of local government policy for peat management in Indonesia. \r\n\r\nDevelopment and dissemination of v2 of CCAFS-Mitigation Options Tool will enhance rapid analysis of mitigation options and priorities.\r\n\r\nCompendium data will enable analysis of trade-offs between emissions reductions and other benefits, such as yields.', 'The most significant work for achieving long-term outcomes was an assessment of gender differentiated roles in dairy supply chains and best practices among implementing organizations for gender equity in East Africa to inform development of the Kenya dairy NAMA.  Gender dimensions were analyzed in the review of INDCs and in the analysis of USAID LED options.   Other activities ensured inclusion of men and women or disadvantaged groups in conducting research or training:   CIFOR in the monitoring of local regulations in Indonesia, IRRI\'s social influence mapping and ILRI\'s training of women scientists to conduct national inventories.'), ('93', '3', '42', '2015', 'Understanding generalizable incentives and innovations for scaling up LED is a work in progress in CCAFS. Developing the evidence to support climate finance remains a priority. Reviews conducted of the economics of AWD in paddy rice and balanced N fertilizer use showed consistent net positive benefits of key mitigation measures due to reduced costs and increased yields, yet the amount of data available is poor and more sophisticated financial analysis for lending projects is still needed. Estimates for the cost of monitoring, reporting and verification were developed, although data is also sparse. A directory for climate finance was compiled and disseminated; there appears to be a high demand for this.  Analysis of barriers and incentives was conducted for scaling up major LED options relevant to USAID. \r\n\r\nCountry-led initiatives are developing pragmatic approaches. Farmers\' perceptions and agronomic and economic incentives for farmers to adopt AWD are being analyzed by IRRI to inform dissemination strategies in Vietnam and Bangladesh. Platforms for scaling up have been identified in both countries, including Loc Troi contract farming in Vietnam and two large-scale development projects in Bangladesh. Governance structures and institutional arrangements were mapped in Vietnam.  In Brazil a GIS analysis quantifying the links between deforestation, land tenure and agricultural intensification suggests that the “Green Municipality” model was effective to reduce deforestation but is limited to promote sustainable and low emissions cattle ranching, so additional incentives are required.', 'Reviews of opportunities to improve women’s participation in and benefits from LED in paddy rice in Vietnam, dairy in Kenya and livestock in Costa Rica developed in collaboration with project leaders showed that dairy in East Africa has the most potential to reduce emissions while also benefitting women.'), ('94', '2', '46', '2015', 'WSU improved the CCAFS Regional Agricultural Forecasting Toolbox (CRAFT), adding models for additional crops and improved AgMIP data translation tools, providing a more open distribution system, and enhancing usability and documentation. \r\nIn EA, ICPAC evaluated climate forecasting and downscaling tools to improve seasonal forecast information, converted probabilistic rainfall forecasts into daily rainfall amounts, and introduced seasonal forecasts of rainfall quantities into the 41st Greater Horn of Africa Climate Outlook Forum (GHACOF41).  IRI trained staff of Meteo-Rwamda in management of ENACTS gridded data sets and development and maintenance of online climate information “maprooms.”  \r\nIn WA, NHMS in Ghana and Mali were trained to improve data quality control and analysis, and introduced to daily rainfall estimation through merging of satellite data with their station data. ANACIM (Senegal) identified major capacity needs for climate data. \r\nIn Colombia, National Agroclimatic Bulletins provided crop management recommendations based on forecasts, and strengthened communication between climate information providers and agricultural user groups. \r\nIn SEA, IRRI tested a beta version of climate-informed, ICT-based, agro advisory services for the Mekong and Red River deltas, recording farmer demographic information to better match information to farmer needs.  ICRAF analyzed relationships between climate and yield data, and mentored NMHS staff to improve forecast information in Vietnam.  ILRI initiated risk mapping for climate-sensitive zoonotic diseases based on a 40-year climate data set.\r\nIn SA, new climate datasets were developed in Nepal and Bangladesh for the CRAFT tool, and used to estimate crop yields and characterize climatic risks at sub-national and local levels.', 'In WA, the development of climate information tailored to farmer needs emphasized building awareness by NHMS of the differing needs associated with gender, wealth and education level.\r\nIn Colombia, efforts to increase farmer feedback to information providers emphasized gender roles and their impact on gender-specific concerns and information needs. \r\nIn SEA, development of climate-related agro-advisory services ensured that at least 20% of participants in plot testing were women, in order to tailor services to the differing need of women and men.'), ('95', '2', '47', '2015', 'In EA, CCAFS (with U. Reading, ICRAF, ICRISAT, FRI) and WFP assessed farmer information needs, trained agricultural extension and other intermediaries in the Participatory Integrated Climate Information Services for Agriculture (PICSA) approach, initiated district-level seasonal Planning and Review workshops, and piloted communication of climate information through rural radio and SMS in target districts in Tanzania and Malawi. \r\nIn WA, U. Reading and other partners trained NGOs and extension agents in northern Ghana on the PICSA approach, and assessed resulting communication and use of information at the farm level.  Results showed that 97% of trained farmers changed their management in response. ANACIM engaged the Union of Rural Community Radios to generate and disseminate downscaled weather and seasonal forecast across Senegal.  \r\nIn LAM, Local Technical Agroclimatic Committees Initiative analyzed forecasts, developed advisories and incorporated these in bulletins in for farmers in Colombia.  Simplified wording was used for bulletins targeting indigenous communities. \r\nIn SEA, IRRI tested a beta version of climate-informed, ICT-based, agro advisory services for the Mekong and Red River deltas, recording farmer demographic information to better match information to farmer needs. ICRAF and CARE developed and piloted the agro-climatic handbook and methods for downscaled agro-climate zone maps, and initiated village/commune-level agroclimate information advisories integrating farmers’ local knowledge. ILRI initiated investigation of the seasonality of climate-sensitive diseases in Vietnam, to inform policies for public health, agriculture and environment.\r\nThe SA RPL assessed feasibility of implementing ICT based agro-advisory system in Climate Smart Villages in Nepal.', 'UF conducted comparative study of gender-specific use of climate services in Kenya and Senegal, and investigated the potential for health clinics to provide information for rural women in Senegal.  \r\nIn EA, baseline and needs assessment surveys in Tanzania and Malawi were disaggregated by gender.  UF assessed progress and provided guidelines for strengthening the benefits of PICSA for women in Tanzania in the GFCS project.  \r\nIn northern Ghana, 40% of the 6000 farmers reached through the PICSA process were women.  Communities of practice formed to co-design, co-test and co-validate climate services are composed of at least 30% women and 30% youth to ensure that climate services that are adapted to needs of women and youth.  \r\nDevelopment of agro-advisory services in Colombia included understanding gender roles throughout the production chain of the key crops. \r\nIn SEA, ICRAF collected gender-differentiated information on men and women farmers’ needs and use of agro-climate information.'), ('96', '2', '48', '2015', 'In WA, index insurance products were designed for Northern Ghana, and a roadmap towards implementation was laid out with the Ghana Agricultural Insurance Program. In Senegal, all major index-based insurance stakeholders took part in a consultation workshop on the role of mobile platforms to support scaling, and developed three collaborative project proposals.  CCAFS and partners (CIMMYT, Pula Advisors) worked with the Nigeria government to draft a roadmap for the development of inclusive insurance for its agriculture sector, and inform GIZ-supported implementation of area-yield and weather index insurance pilots.  \r\nIn LAM, IRI designed prototype index insurance for basic grains in the Dry-Corridor of Colombia, and developed technical guidance for insurance companies to adapt and implement the product. \r\nIn SA, the RPL and partners developed innovative methods that improve the satisfaction of farmers, industry and government in index insurance for rice, pearl millet, soybean and cotton in Maharashtra state.  The Government of Maharashtra has used these improved insurance products to protect one million farmers in 2015.  IFPRI developed a theoretical framework to link insurance with climate-smart technologies.  IWMI initiated development of Index-based Flood Insurance (IBFI) for India (Bihar) and Bangladesh (Sirajganj), through engagement with local communities, and Ministries of Disasters and Agriculture. These agencies are participating in the research and committing in-kind resources to subsidize the pilot IBFI scheme.', 'In WA, a set of gender-sensitive index insurance design materials was developed, tailored to the Northern Region of Ghana, and pre-tested.  \r\nIn LAM, participatory processes to design index insurance included the participation of men and women farmers, to capture both perspectives. \r\nIn SA, gender-disaggregated data were collected to incorporate gender-based differences into the design of Climate-Smart Insurance products.  The development of Index-Based Flood Insurance has involved women and smallholders to identify how they may benefit.'), ('97', '2', '49', '2015', 'In EA, DSSAT crop models have been calibrated using data collected from previous experiments and agricultural sample surveys, and tested to simulate national yields of maize and sorghum in Ethiopia and Kenya using gridded climate and soil data at high resolution.  \r\nIn WA, CRAFT has been adapted to use AGRHYMET’s gridded data sets and preferred crop model, SarraH, for regional crop production forecasting and food security early warning.  AGRHYMET, which is mandated to provide crop monitoring and early warning services regionally, already has substantial experience calibrating, testing and evaluating SarraH.  The Environmental Information System in Cote d’Ivoire developed a comprehensive logical framework, elaborated a list of environmental indicators, developed a robust data collection strategy and chose the appropriate platform capable of hosting the project.\r\nIn LAM, work to improve food security information and decision support focused on studying women’s participation in decision-making processes in community committees at food security monitoring sentinel sites in Guatemala.  \r\nIn SEA, ILRI conducted a literature review to understand the relationship between climate change and zoonotic diseases, to inform the development of early warning and decision support systems in Vietnam.', 'A study of participation in community committees at food security monitoring sentinel sites in Guatemala emphasized women\'s participation in decision-making and control over income.'), ('98', '2', '50', '2015', 'CCAFS contributions to the 42nd session of the UNFCCC Subsidiary Body for Scientific and Technological Advice (SBSTA) included a submitted paper and InfoNote with recommendations on how investment in early warning systems could contribute more to the development of climate-resilient agricultural systems and rural livelihoods in Africa.  \r\nIn WA, CCAFS collaboration with ANACIM to identify challenges and develop strategy for scaling up climate services for agricultural risk management in Senegal informed funding by USAID.  \r\nIn Colombia, publication on the current status of climate services for agriculture, and mapping of communication networks strengthens the knowledge and evidence base for potential future investment.  \r\nIn SEA, ILRI-led studies and information materials on the prevalence of climate-sensitive diseases, and potential environmental and climatic risk factors, paves the way for expanded development of national early warning systems for those diseases.', 'Analysis of climate information needs in Senegal considered specific information needs of women and youth.  Mapping of climate information networks in Colombia used separate focus groups for women and men to capture gender-related differences.'), ('99', '2', '51', '2015', 'A workshop, ‘Strengthening Regional Capacity for Climate Services in Africa’ (Victoria Falls, Zimbabwe), aimed to connect CCAFS work on strengthening climate services capacity through African regional institutions, with the Africa-wide climate research and climate services community at the fifth conference on Climate Change and Development in Africa (CCDA-V).  The FL maintained contact with the leadership of the GFCS, and key individuals at WB and USAID that invest in climate services.', 'Not applicable');
COMMIT;

