INSERT INTO `outcome_synthesis` VALUES ('19', '6', '2015', '66', '13', '21.00', 'National research institutes (KALRO, NARO, SARI) and sub-national organizations across EA are actively testing CSA options using CCAFS science and decision support tools. Building on the Seeds for Needs citizen science experience, Ministry of Agriculture in Ethiopia is developing a CSA manual. In Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda, an interactive tool documenting future seed zonations for the mid-21st century for 13 important agro-forestry species has been provided to national tree seed centres to support seed source selection. In Nyando CSVs, ILRI scientists worked on strengthening the capacity of farmers on small ruminant (SR) breeding and management. In Wote CSVs, government extension officers and Makueni County government are using information from previous and current CCAFS projects (e.g AgMIP, ICRISAT, CIMMYT) on climate variability information, seasonal forecasts with targeted advice on CSA practices to advice farmers. The sorghum-pigeonpea inter-crop has been widely adopted and promoted as climate-smart-technology in drier areas of Makueni (approximate 600 farmers).\r\n\r\nOn policy, results from climate wizard and climate impact were used to develop CSA Country Plans for Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania, Namibia, and Botswana, with the CSA plans integrated into Kenya INDCs and CSA Implementation Guidelines in Tanzania. In Uganda, District development plan for Luweero, adapted through PACCA project.', 'Activities contributing to the outcome integrate gender and social inclusion. These include the TripleA project working with gender inclusive project groups, where more than half of the 597 project group members are women. Farmer-to-farmer training sessions on CSA practices will be carried out by gendered lead-farmer teams, composed of one man and one woman. PEACSA activities addressed gender issues e.g during the household typology research - 50% of respondents in FGDs were women, purposive targeting of participants in field evaluations. During the AGMARK scaling at least 30% of the 1.5m materials distributed targeted women. Data collected are gender-disaggregated and varieties included in released panel are balanced between female and male preferences when differences exist. Teams in charge of site management are encouraged to be gender balanced. At regional level, umbrella CBOs consisting of about 60% women are involved in evaluating crop-related CSA interventions. The ICRAF led project on climate-smart tree sourcing in East Africa, are categorized as gender- and socially neutral because selected tree species were national priorities, and include species that can benefit various typologies of end-users. \r\n\r\nAll existing plans and country programs highlight the importance of considering gender and social inclusion in them for achieving climate smart outcomes.', '', '1.00'), ('20', '6', '2015', '67', '14', '3.00', 'PEACSA is involving public and private actors at national and sub-national levels and generating unforeseen incentives. For instance, agro dealers anticipate that conservation agriculture will enhance sales of herbicides, drought tolerant germ plasm, and related equipment. Also, Acre Africa (one of PEACSA private sector partners),views the planned PEACSA led Agricultural Innovation Platforms as a key platform for enhancing sustainability. The volunteer farmer trainer (VFT) approach established through the East Africa Dairy Development (EADD) project for the dissemination of livestock feed technologies is being institutionalized in producer organizations in Kenya. In Nyando, a baseline survey completed for small ruminants will be used to develop a SR business model. Furthermore, the Kisumu County government, private sector organizations including Rafiki Microfinance, MAGOS enterprises and CBOs are collaborating to develop a business model for sorghum to be scaled up into other administrative divisions of Kisumu and neighboring counties.', 'Gender was prioritized throughout PEACSA activities in 2015. For instance during the AGMARK scaling at least 30% of the 1.5m materials distributed targeted women.  The role of men and women farmers in the VFT approach has been characterized as documented in the ICRAF Working Paper No. 221. Also, Maseno University provided Nyando farmers including the youth and women with mobile phone messaging services for on-farm planning and decision making. The youth and women are involved in managing horticultural \"smart farms\". The ongoing sorghum business model development process involves women, who constitute 60% of the CBO membership.', '', '0.00'), ('21', '6', '2015', '68', '36', '2.00', 'Under the INAPFS CIMMTY-led project, ICPAC generated both seasonal and monthly quantitative forecast outputs and effectively communicated these to stakeholders in the IGAD region, including national meteorological and hydrological services, national disaster management and food security offices and agencies. The new forecasts give a spatial distribution of rainfall amounts across east Africa, contributing to and increasing the usefulness of climate information and early warning in the region. The 41st Greater Horn of Africa Climate Outlook Forum (GHACOF41) for the SOND 2015 season included quantitative rainfall forecasts. Regarding crop index insurance, a feasibility study was undertaken for two index insurance pilots in Nigeria. Maize is one of these pilots, and the project has linked up those designing the pilots with the Drought-Tolerant Maize for Africa project (DTMA) led by CIMMYT and IITA. These two centers are providing technical guidance on supplying the most appropriate drought-tolerant maize varieties to the pilots.', 'CIMMYT and IRI are working with an equity specialist on a paper, looking at the social equity issues (including gender and social inclusion) linked to index insurance. An abstract of the paper \"Cultures of Risk and Security: Farmers, Insurance Innovation and Questions of Equity\" has been accepted for presentation at a conference at the British Museum in London in May 2016 on Anthropology, Weather and Climate Change.', '', '1.00'), ('22', '6', '2015', '69', '38', '0.00', 'A NAMA proposal for Kenya\'s dairy sector will be developed by 2018. No low emission plan developed in 2015.', 'Gender and social inclusion contribution is on-going. Preliminary research on gender and social differentiation in feed and manure management conducted in 2015. Data analysis initiated using EADD data on the gender differences in intra-household decision making in the Kenya dairy sector. A review of best practices to ensure gender equity in the dairy sector planned for 2016, as a specific deliverable to the drafting of the Kenya NAMA. The actual design of NAMA interventions needs to ensure gender equity.', '', '0.00'), ('23', '6', '2015', '70', '50', '9.00', 'Significant progress on the science-policy interface in 2015. The scenarios were used to guide the development of the New Environmental Policy in Tanzania, the Agricultural Policy and the Mechanization Framework in Uganda, both combined later into the Agricultural Sector Plan. The draft Ugandan agriculture sector mainstreaming guidelines that PACCA supported is awaiting approval. Furthermore, Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania, Botswana and Namibia developed climate-smart agriculture framework programs (CSA-FPs) which were successfully validated at national level. Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania subsequently integrated CSA into their INDCs submitted to the UNFCCC in 2015 - publicly available online (at www4.unfccc.int).  The CSA-FPs are available online on the Climate and Agriculture Network for Africa (CANA) (at canafrica.com). Based on multi-stakeholder zonal planning outputs at district level, Rakai and Luwero in Uganda, have integrated climate change priorities in their 5 year development plans.\r\n\r\nICRAF developed an innovative geospatial tool which includes functional relationships described in the peer-reviewed publication that stakeholders can use to explore land use/cover suitability. The Tanzania Meteorology Service is using the PICSA approach to meet the climate information needs of smallholder farmers.', 'Both PACCA and partners\' gender research has been disseminated to stakeholders through the learning alliances (LAs). Members of the LAs are preparing for a high level engagement to address gender gaps in climate change adaptation strategies in March 2016. Policy briefs have been drafted to this effect. M&E results show the need to increase women numbers in the national LAs. At district level, male and female farmers are represented in LA activities and their concerns are integrated in the engagement plans. The national CSA-FPs highlight the integration of gender and youth in the development of CSA interventions through value chain integration. Under the PICSA project, women farmers are included in the trainings sessions and gender is being considered during the development of the prototype apps. In the spatially explicit analyses being developed by ILRI, gender differentiated outputs on some of the key performance indicators have been quantified.', '', '1.00'), ('24', '6', '2015', '71', '52', '1.00', 'In collaboration with COMESA, ACPC/UNECA, CORAF/WECARD and IDRC, three submissions to UNFCCC during SBSTA 42 were made by the African Group of Negotiators (AGN) on i) Early Warning Systems, ii) Risks and Vulnerability in Agricultural Systems, iii) Gender and Climate Change. Specifically, the submissions were made by Sudan on behalf of the AGN as the Chair of the AGN in 2015. CCAFS scientists and partners also worked with the AGN team to prepare a presentation  by the Lead Agriculture Coordinator (from Malawi) of the AGN during the agriculture workshops held during SBSTA in 2015.', 'Working with the AGN, a submission made on the inclusion of gender in the climate change discussions to the UNFCCC during SBSTA 42 in 2015. In addition,  a session was organized to dialogue on gender inclusion in the SDGs and Post COP 21 agreements. CCAFS EA RPL also participated in several gender events, including the Gender, Climate Change and Agriculture Support Programme (GCCASP) organized by COMESA and NEPAD in Lusaka, Zambia and Closing the gender gap in farming under climate change: New knowledge for renewed action held in Paris, France.', 'NA', '0.00'), ('25', '2', '2015', '44', '36', '23.00', '23 institutions have responded to the needs of climate service beneficiaries to create and disseminate climate informed services.\r\n• District agricultural extension services in Tanzania, Malawi and Ghana, Red Cross Malawi, Oxfam Ghana and ADRA Ghana incorporated PICSA into their work with farmers.\r\n•  ICPAC via generating seasonal and monthly quantitative forecast outputs communicated to stakeholders, integrated into GHACOF41 for SOND 2015\r\n• Local Technical Agroclimatic Committee (Cauca-Colombia) gave agroclimatic information to inform decision making\r\n•  Zamorano University and COPECO supported the design of a drought index insurance prototype product for basic grains\r\n•  The Cereal producers association in Colombia, FENALCE, and CORPOICA (NARS) increased dissemination of results and development of user-oriented climate products to support farmer decision-making\r\n•  Agriculture Insurance Company of India and Agriculture Department of Maharashtra adopted methodology for developing rainfall triggers that have higher farmer satisfaction\r\n• Ministries of Disaster and Agriculture in India and Bangladesh are subsidizing Index-Based Flood Insurance products for flood prone areas in their countries \r\n•  Ghana Meteorological Agency and Mali-Meteo implemented ENACTS maprooms \r\n•  FMARD in Nigeria using CCAFS-led roadmap and concept notes to guide piloting of index-based agricultural insurance\r\n• National Environmental Information System in Cote d\'Ivoire was fine-tuned in 2015, in preparation for 2016 launch', 'Gender is being included in projects across regions. In East Africa, CIMMYT and IRI are working on a paper on the link between social equity issues and index insurance. This will inform future index insurance projects impacting institutions and this indicator. The Local Technical Agroclimatic Committee’s index insurance work was inclusive of women. Studies are being conducted in LAM with SESAN and ACF to understand gender dynamics in decision making progresses in the sentinel sites. SA projects on Index-Based Flood Insurance have involved women in order to identify potential benefit to them. Pilot testing in Vietnam included 62% women, which ensures futures services developed to reflect the specific services needed by both men and women farmers. In WA, 40% of PICSA trainees were women. ‘Gender Materials Pack – Assessing the Impact of Agricultural Insurance on Gender Dynamics in Northern Ghana’ was developed to specifically address gender dimensions in index-based insurance. In Tanzania and Malawi, 30% of PICSA trainees were women, and 50% of farmers reached as a result were women.', null, '4.00'), ('26', '2', '2015', '45', '37', '0.46', 'In LAM, money has been allocated to invest in climate services in the agriculture sector of Colombia by the Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development (MADR). Research will be done on agroclimatic forecast, crop modelling improvement considering climate variables, experimental plots in different parts of the country, and support of national policy and action plans. In SEA, negotiations are underway for co-funding of a project on enhancing adaptive capacity of women and ethnic minority smallholder farms.', 'Gender is a component of both the already committed funds and the funds that are under negotiation. The MADR project includes studies with a gender perspective regarding roles in main crop activities. The project in negotiation in SEA includes gender as a main focus.', null, '2.00'), ('27', '5', '2015', '108', '13', '10.00', 'In Latin America, national producer\'s associations are using CCAFS science on soils, crop management, climate and yield, and they have also learned to manage data to improve their decision making processes considering climate variability (Colombiarice producers association, FEDEARROZ). \r\nTools to strengthen knowledge on practices for climate change adaptation of coffee landscapes are being learned and used by coffee cooperatives (ASOBAGRI in Guatemala and PROODECOP in Nicaragua). \r\nLatin American farmers have formulated and started to implement 30 local adaptation plans through a participatory approach identifying and developing context-specific CSA adaptation measures involving both scientific and traditional knowledge (Communities in Los Cerrillos-Cauca Climate-Smart Village in Colombia) and local partners are using crowdsourcing methodologies to reach approximately 2000 farmers directly and 50,000 beneficiaries indirectly in Central America Climate-Smart Villages in Trifinio and Nicaragua.\r\n4 Local Technical Agroclimatic Committees in Colombia are using CSA CCAFS science in their recommendations at local level considering agroclimatic forecasts. CCAFS and CIAT engagement in Colombia contributed to include this initiative as an adaptation measure to the adaptation goals in the INDC. \r\nGuatemala MoA is using the portfolio from the CSA prioritization framework to develop an strategy for donors indicating them the country priorities regarding agriculture and climate change.', 'Women from two communities in Nicaragua have strengthened the required skills to facilitate their sustainable use of Climate-Site Management Systems. Rice smallholder farmers (women and men) in Nicaragua improved their knowledge related to climate, soil and management practices and their effect on yield. In Nicaragua and Peru, gender gaps were identified, particularly in the identification of women as decision maker in production systems, no necessarily recognized as producer. \r\nIn Los Cerrillos-Cauca Climate-Smart Village in Colombia, the participatory approach included the involvement of youth throughout the local planning process by training them in communication skills and GIS tools that support discussions within the families and the community. The planning process explores both men and women perspective and reconciles them in order to consider needs, ideas and challenges regarding gender. \r\nRegarding crowdsourcing methodology, data collected are gender-disaggregated; women participation is encouraged/ensured; specific studies on women\'s access to mobile phone and motivation to participate have been conducted, gender income control indicators have been included in the baseline.', 'The target achieved succeeded the expectations given the work among the various projects and the regional program in providing inputs to key partners on how to implement and use CSA to support their decision making processes.', '1.00'), ('28', '5', '2015', '108', '14', '2.00', 'In Latin America, the efforts during 2015 were focused on active consultations with potential national (ANACAFE, CAFENICA, IICA, Atlantic) and international (IBD, Root Capital, Neumann foundation, SAFE) investors and strategic partners to develop strategies on how to support adaptation in coffee landscapes in Guatemala and Nicaragua, efforts to continue these advances will be made although budget restrictions. \r\nIn adittion, succesful engagement was achieved with coffee and cocoa stakeholders in Peru, in order to support coffee and cocoa value chains by developing climate-smart protfolios contributing to the international quality certification incentives which will be the main focus in 2016.', 'Processes involved a gender perspective by identifying the different needs, views and potential impacts for men and women of the activities done within the projects that are contriguting to this outcome indicator. However, in depth analyisis, as well as, monitoring and avaluation will be developed while the development of the on-going project regarding coffee and cocoa value chains in Peru and Nicaragua.', 'The discrepancy is due to the prioritization of Ghana in the coffee and cocoa value changes due to strategic decisions in terms of outcome and impact achievement, during 2016 the project will be developed in Latin America as planned.', '1.00'), ('29', '5', '2015', '115', '36', '5.00', 'In Latin America communities’ access and use agroclimatic information to inform their decisions according the agroclimatic forecast given in the Local Technical Agroclimatic Committee (Cauca-Colombia) implemented by CCAFS, MoA and local partners. Its participatory approach allows forecasts and recommendations validation in each meeting (main concerns/successes).\r\nAdditionally, farmers in Honduras participated in the design of a drought index insurance prototype product for basic grains led by IRI and SAG (Secretariat of Agriculture and Livestock) supported by Zamorano University and COPECO (government\'s climate-sector providers), which farmers validated and tested in the field through dry run experiments with over 230 farmers in the Dry Corridor. The index captured the 2015 drought, providing confidence of its operability. \r\nClimate services are now being considered as a key variable for decision making process of SESAN (Secretariat for Food and Nutrition) in Guatemala regarding the implementation of new sentinel sites, which includes the evaluation and validation of data generated to alleviate food security considering climate, elaboration of an integrated data analysis instrument and improvement in the presentation of tailored results.\r\nCereal producers association in Colombia, FENALCE and CORPOICA (NARS) have increased their ownership, dissemination of results and development of climate user-oriented products to support farmers decision making.', 'Local Technical Agroclimatic Committee gathers both indigenous communities, local authorities and cooperatives, in which local tradition and knowledge is considered and used as an input. Indigenous communities are represented by both men and women as well as cooperatives. \r\nThe index insurance related activities that were organized in the field were inclusive of women and men producers, even though with a male majority.\r\nIn 2015, Bioversity together with SESAN and ACF designed a study to understand the gender dynamics in decision making processes in the sentinel sites. The study will be finished before April 2016. The results will help to develop a gender strategy for the sentinel site system. \r\nStudy on gender roles, social differentiation, key nodes and mapping information flows in Colombia, this information will be used as baseline to identify gaps and tailor agro-climatic information to the requirements and demands of farmers for their usability to 4500 maize farmers and 3000 bean farmers in Colombia.', 'Given the approach used to support stakeholders with climate services in the countries in Latin America, it was well-accepted since it was responding to main needs that the countries were facing mainly regarding climate variability. This is why indicator target was succeeded satisfactorily.', '0.00'), ('30', '5', '2015', '115', '37', '0.46', 'The Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development (MADR) of Colombia allocated approximately 0.46 millions of dollars to invest in climate services in the agricultural sector in the country supported by CIAT and CCAFS. The engagement with the Colombian government have increased in the last years where CCAFS and CIAT have demonstrated the value added that provides in order to face climate change and variability challenges while strengthening capacity to national organizations. The investment included research on agroclimate forecast, crop modelling improvement considering climate variables, experimental plots in different parts of the country supported by key producers organizations, support national policy and action plans.', 'While developing the main research on the agreement with the Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development (MADR) of Colombia, studies were developed with a gender perspective regarding roles in main crops activities, such as maize and rice.', 'Project within their development achieved to start contributing to this indicator.', '0.00'), ('31', '5', '2015', '121', '38', '3.00', 'CCAFS through CIAT and its partners informed scientifically the formulation of three Mitigation Policies for the Agricultural Sector in Latin America. The coffee NAMA in Costa Rica which is already approved by the NAMA facility for financing, the National Livestock Low Emission Strategy ratified by the Costa Rica government and the Colombia Livestock NAMA submittet to UNFCCC. Key research outputs were used to support the fomulation of these policies such as the Projected Shifts in Coffea arabica Suitability among Major Global Producing Regions Due to Climate Change, Multiclass Classification of Agro-Ecological Zones for Arabica Coffee. the improved pasture potential and rational management as mitigation options, capture potential in soils by pasture systems.', 'The NINO (Colombia) and NAMA concept (Costa Rica) have been designed to ensure that the NAMAs promote gender equity and social inclusion. Costa Rica´s NAMA concept included a description of the activities included into the NAMA that are performed by women and in which women have a role in the decision-making.', 'Given the engagement with national institutions in Costa Rica and Colombia, and the tailored support given by CIAT and its partners to main concerns and needs of the policy formulators, the target achieved was higher than expected.', '1.00'), ('32', '5', '2015', '121', '39', '0.02', 'Although there was no target expected fo 2015 regarding this indicator in Latin America, advances have been made regarding the implementation of the Livestock NAMA in Costa Rica which will lead to pasture improvement, increased livestock productivity and reduced GHG emissions in Chorotega region and in other regions as the NAMA is countrywide and so far the estimation is that the target area (0.02 million has) may have benefited through technology and knowledge sharing using twenty pilot farms in the Chorotega region.\r\nThe research conducted by CIFOR and its partners on improved cattle production systems that could increase productivity while at the same time using better the available natural resources covers an area of (3.210 has). These farms constitute the bases for experimenting systems that will be further scaled up. The project is realizing activities in 10 locations in the Municipality of Paragominas. Out of these, nine are medium-scale farms and one is located in the experimental farm of EMBRAPA in the same municipality.', 'NAMAs have been designed to ensure the promotion of gender equity and social inclusion. Costa Rica´s NAMA concept included a description of the activities iperformed by women and in which women have a role in the decision-making process.', 'Projects within their development achieved to start contributing to this indicator.', '0.00'), ('33', '5', '2015', '126', '50', '3.00', 'CCAFS Latin America has been succesfull in the policy engagement by supporting national policy makers in using science to streghthen their policies on climate change and agriculture. As evidence, CCAFS enabled the dialogue between scientists and decision and policy makers of Colombia to streghthen the formulation of Colombia\'s INDCs and in Costa Rica supported the INDCs formulation process by using the future socioeconomic scenarios methodology, which was also used by the Secretariat of Agriculture and Livestock (SAG) of Honduras to streghthen its National Adaptation Policy for the Agricultural Sector. CCAFS also supported collaborative work with CATIE, CAC and IICA to achieve the Declaration of Central American Coutries supporting CSA announced during COP21.', 'Gender balance, as well as the representation of vulnerable groups, was always taken into account in socioeconomic processes design – and through sub-national public engagements. Publications on the inclusion of gender in climate change policy were developed and disseminated to policy makers in national institutions of Costa Rica, Colombia and Peru, the process of engagement has been a channel to support decision makers the importance of including gender in policies but also how to include them.', 'Committed work with national policy makers and researchers made possible to achieved a higher target in the region regarding this indicator.', '1.00'), ('34', '5', '2015', '126', '52', '2.00', 'At a regional level, CCAFS supported collaborative work with CATIE, CAC and IICA to achieve the Declaration of Central American Coutries supporting CSA announced during COP21. In adittion, CIAT and CCAFS (with FP1 and LAM contribution) supported the World Bank by developing CSA Country Profile for Nicaragua as an input for a WB advisory report for Nicaraguan policy makers, which also includes other CIAT/CCAFS scientific inputs on agricultural sector, climate projections and GHG emissions.', 'Publications on the inclusion of gender in climate change policy were developed and disseminated to policy makers in national institutions of Costa Rica, Colombia and Peru, the process of engagement has been a channel to support decision makers the importance of including gender in policies but also how to include them.', 'Committed work with national policy makers and researchers made possible to achieved a higher target in the region regarding this indicator.', '0.00'), ('35', '8', '2015', '143', '13', '15.00', 'Several centers have actively involved in identification, prioritization, testing and evaluation of CSA technologies, practices and services in different agro-ecological zones of South Asia using methods and decision support tools developed by CCAFS.  CIMMYT in collaboration with NARS has tested and evaluated different interventions in the CSVs in Haryana, Punjab, Gujarat and Bihar States of India. Partnership work among CCAFS, CIMMYT, IFPRI, IWMI and NARS in Haryana resulted in state government’s commitment to develop 400 CSVs. Similarly, a framework for evaluation of alternate CSV approaches is now being evaluated in several locations of Nepal in collaboration with local stakeholders.  Significant progress has been made in integrating the CSV plans with the local development plans for resource leverages and co-investment to promote CSA in the villages. \r\n\r\nBioversity has actively engaged with 12 rural agri science centres in India to mainstream the CSA citizen science approach in government’s agricultural programs. IWMI has installed water harvesting measures to manage surplus floodwater for irrigation. WorldFish in Bangladesh has implemented CSA technologies such as fish micro habitat development and promotion of Sorjan agriculture in the coastal agriculture. In summary, CSV approach is gaining ground in scaling out CSA technologies, practices and services. In South Asia.', 'Gender and social inclusion is one of the impact evaluation criteria for CSA/CSVs projects in South Asia. Majority of the projects related to CSA/CVSs have identified, prioritized and developed portfolios of climate smart technologies, practices and services considering the feasibility and preferences of gender and farm typology. Women’s involvement and adoption benefits for small and marginal farmers were explicitly considered in the CSA/CSV projects implementation process. \r\n\r\nMainstreaming gender and youth in the CSV approach has been a major priority in some projects. For instance, about 50% CSV pilots in Nepal are managing by Women Farmers Group and all CSVs are ensuring the active participation of young farmers and smallholders. Similarly, in India, a robust gender-responsive framework for targeting and implementing climate smart agricultural practices in the CSVs has been developed and implemented in order to ensure the participation of at least 40% women and other socially differentiated groups in project activities. In summary, current projects ensure that the Climate Change-Gender-Food Security nexus has been well considered during project designing, implementing and evaluation.', 'Due to large budget cuts, many projects could not implement their activities in some proposed locations, some projects cut down their activities and proposed partnership between CG centers and local partners jeopardized.', '1.00'), ('36', '8', '2015', '148', '36', '6.00', 'Designing and implementation of improved crop insurance products for mitigation of climatic risks in agriculture has been major priority area. CCAFS-SA has developed an innovative methodology for developing rainfall triggers with higher satisfaction of farmers, industry and government in collaboration with Agriculture Insurance Company of India and Agriculture Department of Maharashtra for key crops (rice, pearl millet, soybean and cotton) in Maharashtra state. The Government of Maharashtra has used these improved insurance products to protect one million farmers in 2015 alone. Similarly, a theoretical framework of climate-smart insurance has been developed by IFPRI to design insurance products for the farmers who implement climate smart technologies and practices in particular crop. \r\n\r\nDevelopment of Index-based Flood Insurance (IBFI) products for the flood prone areas in India (Bihar) and Bangladesh (Sirajganj) has been started. Advance level engagement and communication have been done with local communities, officials as well as intermediate and high level Ministries in Disasters and Agriculture agencies. The agencies in Bihar and Bangladesh are participating in the research and committing in-kind resources to implement IBFI scheme by subsidizing insurance premium for farmers. This indicates increasing acceptance of the program and potential of scaling up in next project cycle.', 'Gender dis-aggregated data has been collected to incorporate gender issues in climate smart insurance products. Potential of linking up gender and social inclusion with national programs in flood insurance has been explored. Additionally, the ongoing project on Index-based Flood Insurance (IBFI) has involved women and smallholders to identify potential benefit from the project to them.', 'Due to large budget cuts, some projects could not implement their activities in the proposed locations.', '1.00'), ('37', '8', '2015', '149', '38', '0.00', 'All mitigation related projects in South Asia have focused on measurement of GHG reduction potentials in agriculture through the implementation of climate smart technologies and practices. Emission reduction potential under different tillage, residue and nutrient management practices were quantified in dryland/rainfed and irrigated agriculture systems. Various scenarios for GHG mitigation in agriculture sector have been developed based on the inputs from stakeholders in India that could help to identify emission hotspot and mitigation option. Additionally, CSV projects in the region have included several climate smart technologies and practices that could have co-benefits of GHG emission reduction.', 'A linkage between gender and GHG mitigation has not explored and was not a priority of the projects in SA.', '', '0.00'), ('38', '8', '2015', '150', '50', '4.00', 'CG Centers and national partners have actively involved policy engagement and communication by using CCAFS’s Science products. IFPRI has prepared inventories of policies for CSA in Bangladesh, India, Nepal and Sri Lanka. CCAFS has been coordinating scenarios for Bangladesh National Adaptation Plan for agriculture. IFPRI and CCAFS’s scenarios team has significantly engaged with key policy makers to include CCAFS’s inputs into country’s 7th Five-Year Plan. IFPRI and a local partner have used CCAFS-SA products to develop and implement a US$ 3 million pilot project for CSVs in Madhya Pradesh of India. \r\n\r\nDecision support tools like CSAP were used in formulation of national climate change adaptation plan (draft document for Bangladesh) for setting technology-crop portfolio considering regional targets and local biophysical resources and climate risks. Scaling up CSA project funded by CDKN in Nepal has been using CSAP and Climate Analogue tools to develop CSA scaling up and implementation plan for Nepal.', 'Mainstreaming gender and social inclusion in the CSA adaptation and mitigation policies and institutions has been a focus of FP4 related project in South Asia. In preparing policy inventories in each country, IFPRI and CCAFS-Scenario working group have highlighted the (often missing) gender sensitivity of policies for promoting climate smart agriculture. Gender and social inclusion is a major component in the scaling up CSA project funded by CDKN in Nepal. This project is integrating gender and social issues in the draft CSA scaling up and implementation plan for Nepal.', 'The focus of the centres seems to have deviated from developing policies that can scale up CSA on a large scale to small win-win situations.', '1.00'), ('39', '1', '2015', '13', '13', '9.00', 'Strategic support to 9 national and 23 subnational level initiatives: \r\nUSAID Feed the Future in orienting its future programming towards encompassing CSA principles; Multiple CSA donors through a CSA metrics database and indicator selection framework; Government of Mali through CSA prioritization; ECOWAS though the development of a CSA intervention Framework ; COMESA through 5 CSA Country Plans; Government of Kenya by integrating CSA into the INDCs and World Bank CSA loan through support on a CSA country profile; World Vision though supporting their Niger strategy; Colombian productive sector adaptation through support to MoA and establishing INDC targets for agriculture; Government of Guatemala through CSA prioritization and development of Ag&Climate strategy for donors. \r\n\r\nNARS/Local agricultural departments across 22 CSVs actively tested CSA options and used CCAFS decision support tools to promote scaling via extension services and local development plans: India’s State government committed to develop 500 CSVs and is using CCAFS-informed LAPA for scaling through the State-Action-Plan; Multi-level CSA planning was undertaken in Colombia, Guatemala, Mali and India; Ethiopian Bureaus of agriculture and CATIE used the CSA citizen science approach; Provincial Advisory Group was established in Vietnam and Philippines‘ CSV included in the Philippines’ Adaptation and Mitigation in Agriculture Program', '2015 efforts to inform institutions’ prioritization and implementation of equitable best bet CSA options and support mainstreaming of GSI materialized in:\r\n\r\nHigh-level support to strategic partners’ initiatives:   \r\n• WB: Gender and Stakeholder Involvement module (CSA-101 website)\r\n• WB-IFAD-FAO Sourcebook: Module 18 Gender and CSA \r\n• UNESCO: Science Report Chapter: Global trends in Gender and Science&Engeneering \r\n\r\nTargeting/planning/prioritization/scaling/M&E tools:\r\n• USAID-CSA programing tool. \r\n• Gender related indicators included in prioritization processes (Guatemala, Mali) \r\n• Gender aspects included in the household typology and Risk-household-options research\r\n• Participatory gender and youth-responsive methodologies and gender task analysis embedded in local planning and prioritization (Vietnam,Colombia)\r\n• Youth involvment in local planning fostered through communications and GIS trainings in Colombia\r\n• Gender-disaggregated data and varieties tested through the Crowdsourcing methodology (India, Ethiopia,Central America).\r\n\r\nCSA evaluation, evidence-building and CSV approach:\r\n• Gender-responsive framework for targeting/implementation used in WA and SA, where majority of projects developed CSA portfolios considered gender feasibility, preferences and farm typology.\r\n• CSA practices most relevant to women documented for scaling-out by local/sub-national Governments\r\n• Women’s unions key role played in the CSA prioritization (SEA), CSV management (Nepal) and evaluations (Kenya, India)\r\n• Women and youth farmers accessed the Innovation Fund through CBOs(Kenya)', null, '6.00'), ('40', '1', '2015', '14', '14', '3.00', 'Progress was focused on ensuring use of CCAFS science and engaging with public-private partners and programs to lay the ground for designing and implementing CSA incentive-mechanisms, including:   \r\n\r\n- Discussions with WB and CARE to pilot novel finance options \r\n\r\n- Regional engagement with:\r\n•agro-dealers and Acre Africa to promote CA and creating opportunities for investments; farmer cooperative used volunteer-farmer-training in their rural advisory services to promote use of fodder shrubs as CSA option (EA)\r\n\r\n•the WACDEP programme incorporated CCAFS-research results in the development of the Integrated Flood Management investment plan; ECOM Agroindustrial Corp’s to uptake project outcomes; ESOKO company, CSIR-SARI and Ghana-Met explorative work payable ICT-transferred climate-smart information; Rainforest Alliance reviewing adjustments to training materials (WA)\r\n\r\n•ANACAFE, CAFENICA, IICA, Atlantic, IBD, Root Capital, Neumann foundation, SAFE investors to develop adaptation strategies (Guatemala and Nicaragua) and coffee/cocoa portfolios contributing to international quality certification incentives (Peru)\r\n\r\n•local governments in 5 SEA-CSVs committed to align development plans and financially support suitable CSA T&Ps.\r\n \r\nCSA-led business models identified for scaling, on: small-ruminants and sorghum with the Kisumu County government, Rafiki Microfinance, MAGOS enterprises and CBOs (EA); water storage and livestock interventions (WA); wheat and maize system (India); higher starch content cassava(SEA)', 'Contribution to evidence-building to support gender-sensitive design of CSA-led incentive mechanisms and business models included: \r\n\r\nIn EA\r\n•Characterizing the role of men and women farmers in the VFT approach; \r\n•Sorghum business model development process involved women (60% of the CBOs)\r\n•Research on equitable and gender focused opportunities for CSA investments through local investment partnerships\r\n•Youth and women involved in managing horticultural \"smart farms\" and accessing mobile phone messaging services for on-farm planning and decision making\r\n•Ready to use CSA-information targeting increased use efficiency of agricultural inputs (AGMARK-Cimmyt) distributed to at least 400000 women across 9 Kenyan counties. \r\n\r\nLAM\r\n•Gender perspective and potential impacts of climate-smart cocoa/coffee value-chains identified for men and women \r\n\r\nWA\r\n•Social and gender groups are taken into account in all projects from inventory stage to validation. \r\n•For the work on cocoa, gender analysis initiated with a focus on youth and land inheritance led by IITA.\r\n\r\nSEA\r\n•Facilitated access of women to inputs to agricultural production. These groups will likely be given access to the \"community innovations fund (Philippines)\r\n\r\nSA\r\n•Inclusion of small and marginal farmers and development of gender segregated data in relation to CSA activities', null, '3.00'), ('41', '3', '2015', '38', '38', '7.00', 'CCAFS science informed three mitigation policies in Latin America (Costa Rica\'s coffee NAMA and livestock low emissions strategy and Colombia\'s livestock NAMA), three work plans related to upscaling mitigation in rice (CCAC multistakeholder proposals in Vietnam, Bangladesh and Colombia, albeit proposals were led by CG centers) and Mongolia\'s INDC (inclusion of livestock).', 'Four plans explicitly included gender and social inclusion elements and women were directly involved as 50% of beneficiaries in the pilot project introducing new sheep breeds in Mongolia. The NINO (Colombia) and NAMA concept (Costa Rica) were designed to promote gender equity and social inclusion.  Two CCAC proposals included strong gender components through participatory technology evaluation and engagement of the Women\'s Union in Vietnam.  The Kenya NAMA preparations included analysis of best practices for gender equity.  Gender benefits are most evidence in projects with direct farmer-level impacts.\r\n\r\nIndependent gender research supported by F3 in 2015 demonstrated that opportunities for women\'s participation and benefits were strong in dairy systems in East Africa. Cheesemaking in Costa Rica is led by women, but the LED impacts appear minor at first analysis. Women\'s involvement in southern Vietnam is most important in terms of influencing husband\'s decisions and in N. Vietnam, in terms of reducing women\'s labor through collaboration with water management cooperatives.', null, '1.00'), ('42', '3', '2015', '39', '39', '7.00', 'LED plans described under ID38 have ambitious scales of impact, especially the CCAC workplans for scaling up AWD in Bangladesh, Vietnam and Colombia, which together constitute the majority of the potentially affected area (6.98 mil ha). Full implementation is unlikely though by 2019, especially as CCAC budget cuts will delay Colombia\'s and CIAT\'s efforts. More realistic levels of implementation are more strongly evident in Costa Rica\'s  Livestock NAMA which can be expected to reduce emissions on 0.02 mil ha based on 20 pilot farms.  CIFOR\'s activities in Brazil likewise will affect 0.003 ha of farms undertaking initial trials.', 'Activities in Bangladesh and Vietnam include provisions for involving women in technology development and (in Colombia as well) monitoring gender and social inclusion outcomes. NAMA\'s in Costa Rica and Colombia include provisions for promoting gender equity and social inclusion.  See ID38 as well. In most sites, gender considerations are mostly about safeguards for avoiding harm to women and recognizing that women and men often make joint decisions as household units.   In most sites, we have yet to identify strong incentives and options for women\'s engagement that would not result in some tradeoffs in interventions to reduce emissions.', null, '0.50'), ('43', '9', '2015', '87', '13', '15.00', 'Local partners have started testing various community-specific CSA practices.  Results of the Situation Analysis and Needs Assessment and the CSV adaptation plans being developed were presented to various government agencies and stakeholders in Vietnam (DARD, Commune People Committee, Farmer’s Union), Laos (PAFO, DAFO, Phonsung Agriculture) and Cambodia (Department of Agricultural Extension, Commune Council).  \r\nUnder the CIAT project, farmer associations and local agricultural departments in the 5 CSVs used the scoring card developed by Bioversity to prioritize potential CSA T&Ps. Participatory meetings with the CSVs, and the provincial and district DARD could result in good outcomes in 2016. \r\nIn the IRRI project, vegetable producer groups self-organized in 4 CSVs. The DAE conducted a commune-level Agro-Ecosystem Analysis for Prek Norin commune in Cambodia, where CSV Rohal Suong is located. The Prek Norin Commune Council chief then requested that Participatory Land Use Planning (PLUP) be carried out for his commune, after participating in village-scale activity.\r\n\r\nLocal government partners were directly engaged in the ICRAF project (e.g PH: MAO, MPDO, MSWDO, MDRRMO; VN: CDARD, DONRE, Ha Tinh Farmers Union). In the Philippines, the project site is among the pilot sites of the Philippines’ Adaptation and Mitigation in Agriculture (AMIA) Program.', 'The roles of men and women have been considered in setting up CSA demonstrations for testing and the outscaling/upscaling of CSA practices. Women’s unions play an important role, especially in the CSA prioritization process in the CSVs. Poor and marginalized farmers participated in the project and they engaged very actively in all activities. In both the Philippines and Vietnam, two CSA practices most relevant to women were selected for up- and out-scaling. Households that were given access to additional water resources for food production during the dry season in the Mekong Delta include balanced numbers of men and women.', 'Only half of the expected targets were achieved by the CIAT project on developing the CSA portfolio and prioritizing the CSA interventions due to its delayed start in July 2015. Other projects under FP1 did not set targets for this indicator, but still contributed to this outcome as they approached and influenced a number of local public and private sector stakeholders. IIRR and ICRAF have already informed international agencies and partners (i.e. FAO, IFAD, GIZ) of the ongoing site-based action research in Vietnam and the Philippines', '0.00'), ('44', '9', '2015', '87', '14', '0.00', 'The projects did not set any targets contributing towards this indicator in 2015', 'The projects did not set any targets contributing towards gender and social inclusion for this indicator in 2015.', 'The projects did not set any targets contributing towards this indicator in 2015', '0.00'), ('45', '9', '2015', '88', '14', '7.00', 'In Ma CSV, owners of processing plants confirmed paying higher prices for cassava with higher starch content. They also strongly support the cassava-grass strips model. Subnational and local governments in 5 CSVs have committed to align their development plans with and financial support for CSA T&Ps that are suitable and/or potential with their strategic development plans. At various meetings, Yen Binh and Yen Bai DARDs offered financial support for good CSA T&Ps and collaborated with CIAT in formulating policies that would support CSA implementation in the districts and provinces. This will take effect in the implementation phase in 2016.\r\n\r\nThe development of \"community innovations fund\" framework was maintained at level of discussion among team due to budget limitation and will be actively pursued once issues of financial resources are resolved', 'Gender-sensitive CSA practices and techniques were given emphasis when introduced to the local partners and stakeholders. Women groups were targeted with gender-sensitive CSA practices (e.g. livestock raising and home gardens) in the Philippines by facilitating better access of women to inputs to agricultural production. These groups will likely be given access to the \"community innovations fund”. In the CSVs across Southeast Asia, the women and the poor were provided with suitable seed varieties and technical guidance. Site visits were conducted to help these groups learn diversified production systems to improve their household value chain by applying new production strategies.', 'CCAFS-SEA targeted to engage sub-national offices of agriculture ministries in the Philippines and Vietnam on the development of villages as proof-of-concept sites for CSA upscaling, however, only the Philippine government agencies were engaged last year. Due to budget limitations, the \"community innovations fund\" was discussed but not implemented. Other project activities were also delayed, thus the discrepancies in the expected and achieved targets for last year. The integration of CSA practices in the CSVs was delayed but we were able to approach several public and private sectors at different levels for future engagement and promotion of CSA interventions.', '0.00'), ('46', '9', '2015', '89', '36', '2.00', 'ILRI’s activities in Vietnam consisted of conducting systematic literature reviews of the relationship between climate-sensitive zoonotic diseases and climate change and identifying temporal patterns of these diseases. The results would be useful in developing policies related to public health, agriculture and environment. ILRI and the national partners also plan to collect agricultural and human samples from six provinces to better understand the epidemiology of these diseases. \r\n\r\nICRAF developed agro-climate zone maps and agro-climatic handbooks integrated with local knowledge that will serve as tools to support the provision of equitable climate services for farmers. These tools are currently piloted in project sites.  Mentoring of the national meteorological services staff of their provincial counterparts has started to decentralize a more user-relevant scale of agroclimatic zone maps and seasonal advisories. In Ha Tinh province, researchers have initiated stakeholder consultations which have generated interest in improving province-wide forecast systems. \r\n\r\nThe IRRI project activities focused on consultations and developing partnerships with concerned stakeholders towards achieving targets in future years..', 'There was a good representation of women in the pilot testing of the agro-advisory services that IRRI developed for rice farmers in Vietnam. Of the 507 rice farmers who participated in the pilot testing, 315 or  62% were women. Responses from these women farmers ensure that services developed or yet to be developed would reflect the specific services needed by men and women farmers. National and local partners would then be motivated as well to target the use of the agro-advisory services with consideration of appropriate gender needs and social inclusion. Meanwhile, for the planned survey on farmer awareness of climate-sensitive diseases, ILRI ensures that results shall provide insights on the differences of farmers’ awareness based on gender, socio-economic factors, educational level and other vital components.', 'In Vietnam and Laos, there is very little information available about the diseases (i.e., Japanese Encephalitis, leptospirosis and aflatoxins) that the ILRI project is focused on. The researchers, in collaboration with the national partners, are planning to collect agriculture products and animal and human samples from six provinces across the Vietnam to better understand the epidemiology of these diseases.', '0.00'), ('47', '9', '2015', '89', '37', '0.00', 'Negotiations are ongoing for possible co-funding for the ICRAF project on enhancing adaptive capacity of women and ethnic minority smallholder farmers in Vietnam.', 'The emphasis of the ICRAF project on gender and ethnic minorities has attracted interest from donors. The baseline survey along with the other strategies was conducted to come up with a well-informed and a results-based project management. The results of the baseline study highlighted the areas where agro-climate information interventions by gender would be relevant.', 'There are no discrepancies regarding the expected and actual targets of the projects for the indicator this reporting period.', '0.00'), ('48', '9', '2015', '90', '38', '3.00', 'Through collaboration with local partners, data on the agronomic benefits of alternate wetting and drying (AWD) were collected and farmers\' perceptions toward different mitigation options are being analyzed. Work plans for Vietnam have been developed by two consortia including ministries for agriculture through the joint project of IRRI and the CCAC. The work plans target opportunities for changing conventional water management to AWD on the large-scale. These opportunities have been identified in the multi-stakeholder workshops and were informed by other CCAFS science outputs. With CCAFS support, national partners in Vietnam submitted their low-emission plan for scaling up implementation of AWD in paddy rice to the CCAC. The plan targets the approximately 11 million irrigated rice farmers in Mekong Delta.\r\nIn the CIFOR project on reducing GHG emissions from oil palm development, improvement in technical options was made with progress in the development of HCV/HCS combined methodologies but these remain to be applied and tested in the field. There has been improved knowledge of the implementation of the local regulation for peat land development which hopefully will be revised based on these lessons and preliminary assessment. HCV/HCS toolkits were disseminated in the framework of other projects and programs.', 'In Indonesia, villages were actively involved in the field surveys and in monitoring GHG reduction emissions from oil palm development. In Vietnam, the country work plan incorporated participatory approaches to enable women to participate in achieving inclusive outcomes based on the assessment of incentives and supporting ministries for scaling up mitigation. The IRRI-CCAC project in Vietnam incorporates an engagement strategy with the Women\'s Union', 'CIFOR- and IFPRI-led projects were able to achieve the expected targets. For the IRRI-CCAC project, although no target was set, two country work plans for Vietnam and Bangladesh have been developed. The FP3 project that was implemented in partnership primarily with non-CG centers had set 8 targets but 3 contributions were achieved, of which, one contribution is from Vietnam', '0.00'), ('49', '9', '2015', '90', '39', '0.00', 'CCAFS facilitated Vietnam’s submission of its implementation plan for alternate wetting and drying (AWD) in paddy rice to the Climate and Clean Air Coalition (CCAC). Vietnam\'s plan to target 11 million paddy rice farmers in the Mekong Delta; a conservative target estimate (reaching 25% of farmers, 0.5 ha each) would be 1.375 million ha', 'CCAFS provided inputs in the submitted AWD work plan to CCAC, which was developed with the engagement of the Women’s Union in Vietnam. Monitoring of gender equity outcomes has been included in project evaluation plans. IRRI considers the involvement of women in project activities to achieve inclusive outcomes', 'CCAFS set a narrow target (10,000 ha) for three focus countries, including Vietnam. CIFOR targeted to work with three private companies in Indonesia but contract with the Aid environment was terminated because of non-performance. There was difficulty in involving private companies to apply their HCV/HCS methodology and secure a Memorandum of Understanding for zero deforestation commitment. Other projects did not target this indicator for 2015', '0.00'), ('50', '9', '2015', '91', '50', '4.00', 'In Cambodia, two new policy processes focused on business were initiated and a scenario session was organized with the Cambodia National Assembly on CSA futures. Results of these processes are being taken forward by the CNA Working Group 3 with CCAFS support. Meanwhile, the Philippines’ NEDA gives premium to the information that will be generated from the modelling outputs developed by IFPRI in providing guidance on appropriate investment policies for Medium-Term Philippine Development and the National Climate Change Action Plans. \r\n\r\nFor the PIRCCA Project in Vietnam, CCAFS supported the national consultation on INDC for agriculture prior to Vietnams’ submission. The project also actively participated in drafting the proposal for the restructuring of rice sector of the country. CCAFS also supported the development of Myanmar’s CSA strategy which has recently been launched by the Ministry of Agriculture and Irrigation (MOAI).', 'Project activities are formulated in such a way that gender and social inclusion contributions are recognized towards the outcome. IFPRI anticipates that the publication of the book on “The Future of Philippine Agriculture: Scenarios, Policies and Investments under Climate Change,” with a chapter on gender adaptation strategies will influence the policymakers of the Philippine government in mainstreaming gender and social inclusion in future climate change policy directions. \r\n\r\nFor the PIRCCA project, results of their gender study which determines gender differences with regard to climate change perception and adaptation strategies in Vietnam has been published on the CCAFS website. Results show that no apparent differences in climate change perception and adaptation strategies were observed between men and women in the area of study. However, the slight differences in men’s and women’s coping strategies during climate stresses imply the potential areas to be explored in order to address gender and social inclusion disparities. Results also identified the most common climate stresses in different regions and the potential climate-smart practices that can be taken into account in formulating site-specific policies', 'The University of Oxford which targeted to contribute to two national policies has actually supported three policies in Cambodia. IFPRI was able to deliver its target. However, none of the two PIRCCA targets was achieved in this reporting period. \r\n\r\nThe CCAFS project on macro-scale governance and institutions analysis is expected to support the development of one policy in 2015. However, this was not achieved.  Although Vietnam has undertaken national food system policies that consider climate change, it is not at the results of CCAFS interventions', '0.00'), ('51', '9', '2015', '91', '52', '4.00', 'CCAFS has established a strong partnership with the ASEAN-CRN, and opportunities for collaboration through policies, institutions and information flows were further highlighted during the 1st ASEAN-CRN Action Planning meeting. Convincing the ASEAN member states to develop and/or replicate existing policy analyses at the national and local levels will serve as a significant support for the achievement of PIRCCA. \r\nCCAFS co-organized a regional consultation workshop with SEARCA and CIAT towards the development of the Umbrella Program on Climate Change Adaptation and Mitigation (CChaM) in Southeast Asia for an Inclusive and Sustainable Agriculture and Rural Development, and this resulted in the formulation of CChAM framework. Anchored on the ASEAN Multi-sectoral Framework on Climate Change (AFCC), the CChAM framework will serve as platform for collaborative R&D, knowledge management, and capacity development on CC adaptation and resiliency in SEA. \r\nCCAFS partnered with the World Wildlife Fund to provide recommendations for the ADB Natural Capital investment document based on the Southeast Asia scenarios. A concept note for the use of scenarios for ASEAN CSR has been approved and is being implemented by the Cambodian government. With Oxfam Asia, a scenario process on climate adaptation was organized focusing on the Philippines and Bangladesh.', 'Gender balance and representation of vulnerable groups were always considered in the design of workshops conducted and in sub-national engagements', 'Three organizations, including WWF, ASEAN CSR and Oxfam Asia, have used CCAFS scenarios results as outcomes of a FP4 project. Another regional project did not indicate an expected target but clearly, the region performed well in this aspect by establishing significant collaborations under this umbrella program.', '0.00'), ('52', '7', '2015', '53', '13', '7.00', '7 national and subnational development initiatives and public institutions that prioritize and inform project implementation of equitable best bet CSA options are using CCAFS science and decision support tools. For instance, through the WA Regional Program and through a bi-lateral USAID project mapped to P4S, CCAFS scientists and partners served as the technical specialists for an ECOWAS forum on climate-smart agriculture sponsored by USAID in May 2015. CCAFS science on CSA was used to inform the development of an CSA intervention Framework for WA and the creation/structuring of workstreams. This set up the relationship for future engagements with ECOWAS on CSA. Furthermore, P4S provided technical information to iNGO partner (World Vision) to support their new Niger strategy. The information developed for Niger served as an early testbed for P4S\' RHO (Risk-Household-Options) modeling framework (see Lamanna et al. CCAFS InfoNote). In West Africa, a synthesis report on the current status of CSV models developed is being produced to foster the dissemination and adoption of best bet CSA options in the region. In respect of cocoa production, two producers\' organisations (Kuapa Kokoo and Agro-Eco) in Ghana are now using shade trees on the recommendation by CCAFS scientists to improve productivity levels.', 'The selection of farmers as part of activities geared towards building climate-smart farming systems through integrated water storage and crop-livestock interventions, included men and women. In Mali there were 100% women in the dry season farming activities, and 100% men in the wet season. In Burkina Faso, the were 40% female participation. Also, the research being conducted on best bet CSA options in West Africa involved the use of a methodological document developed by ILRI which foresees that all social groups and genders are considered from the inventory stage up to the testing and validation stages. Moreover, gender outcomes are being developed and integrated as part of the RHO approach. In a bid to improve the gender research strategies of CCAFS West Africa partners, CCAFS developed and implemented with NARS partners three gender research activities to fill the gaps of knowledge in terms of gender and climate change in West Africa. These research activities included (1) gender empowerment with climate information in Ghana, (2) gender empowerment with Cacia tora in Niger and (3) gender empowerment with non timber forest products in Senegal. Lastly, shade tree advise for cocoa production takes the needs of both men and women farmers into considerations.', '', '2.00'), ('53', '7', '2015', '53', '14', '3.00', 'In Ghana, CCAFS Science is being used to promote climate smart approaches by public-private actors. For instance, active engagement with the WACDEP programme  has resulted in identification of information needs by WACDEP and in incorporating CCAFS research results in the WACDEP process of developing IWRM investment plan for the White Volta basin (northern Ghana). In addition, ECOM confirmed as partner in Ghana is willing to work on uptake of project outcomes with network of 100,000 farmers. In respect of cocoa production, there is incorporation of project exposure mapping results by the Kuapa Kokoo cooperative (100,000 members) while Rainforest Alliance is reviewing adjustments to training materials based on exposure gradient maps. Also, ESOKO company has been working with CSIR-SARI and Ghana-Met to explore the willingness to pay for climate-smart information (weather and seasonal forecasts, CSA technologies) which could be brought to scale if cost-effective and affordable to farmers.', 'Social and gender groups are taken into account in all projects from inventory stage  to validation. For the work on cocoa, gender analysis was initiated in 2015 with a focus on youth and land inheritance led by IITA.', '', '1.00'), ('54', '7', '2015', '54', '36', '3.00', 'CCAFS through IRI and ICRISAT helped Ghana Meteorological Agency and Mali-Meteo set up their own IRI\'s Data Library (DL) and maprooms (http://maps.meteo.gov.gh:89/maproom; http://197.155.140.164). Through University of Reading, ICRAF, Ghana Met. Agency and AIMS, the PICSA approach was deployed in 10 districts in Northern Ghana reaching 140 communities, an est. 6,000 farmers (40% female). A follow up M&E analysis revealed changes in farmers practice for 97% of trainees. University of Reading, ICRAF and ICRISAT joined forces to translate the full PICSA field manual (https://ccafs.cgiar.org/publications/participatory-integrated-climate-services-agriculture-picsa-field-manual#.VtmBSTaviFc) into French in preparation for scaling out to Senegal and Mali (March 2016) and possibly Burkina Faso later on. Moreover, ANACIM and ICRISAT helped an estimated 7.4 million smallholders in 2015 to access climate services through 82 rural radios members of URAC (https://cgspace.cgiar.org/handle/10568/68144) while CCAFS through IRI and CIMMYT developed concept notes and a 4-year roadmap, and supported South-South exchange (https://cgspace.cgiar.org/rest/bitstreams/59174/retrieve) in order to assist Nigeria’s FMARD ambitious plan to support 14.5 million smallholders with ambitious and inclusive insurance schemes. Two value chain development programs in Burkina Faso and Senegal are using climate information services to reduce risk and increase input use (fertilisers, seeds). This resulted into increased productivity and economic benefit.', 'Gender and social inclusion is inherently built into the deployment of all activities, where capacitation is directed to both men and women. For example, 17 female radio communicators were trained under 426 in Senegal in the interpretation and dissemination of seasonal forecast information. Again, 40% of PICSA trainees were women. Further some activities specifically addressed gender dimensions of index-based insurance, e.g. through the production of a \'Gender Materials Pack - Assessing the Impact of Agricultural Insurance on Gender Dynamics in Northern Ghana\'.', '', '2.00'), ('55', '7', '2015', '55', '50', '7.00', 'In Ghana, a national CSA action plan (2016-2020) is developed to strengthen the operation of the country\'s national climate change policy. Additionally, Ghana Met is using the PICSA approach to meet farmers\' need for climate services. In Mali and Senegal, local scenarios and the ASSAR project outcomes have informed the refinery of local policies to integrate climate change and food security dimensions. Meanwhile, the Senegalese Ministry of Agriculture is now using CIS as an agricultural input that guides yearly agricultural action planning. In Burkina Faso, a new scenario-guided planning process was initiated with the government through SP-CSPA, to develop the new plan for rural sector development (PNSR). What was exceptional is that this was a cross-CRP effort, led by CCAFS with FTA, WLE and Dryland Systems – where integrated research plans were made to complement government plans. Through the science-policy platform in Mali, two major CSA options have been identified and evidenced as candidate options for large scale investement. WA scenarios expanded to provide inputs to a UNU project which provides direct recommendations to ECOWAS. Further, CCAFS knowledge supported ECOWAS to now effectively mainstream CSA into regional and national agricultural policies through the CSA alliance (WACSAA) and implementation Framework.', 'In Ghana, both men and women farmers were included in the PICSA trainings and the development of the prototype apps. In addition, gender was mainstreamed in the development processes of the national CSA action plan of Ghana as well as the West Africa CSA alliance. Similarly, gender balance, as well as the representation of vulnerable groups, was always taken into account in workshops and the scenario-guided planning process that led to the development of the new PNSR – plan for rural sector development in Burkina Faso. During the implementation of the project: \"Capacitating science-policy exchange platforms to mainstream climate change into national agricultural and food security policy plans\", a social differentiation study was conducted to map the different categories of stakeholder in the districts targeted. Further, in 2015, 21%; 33% and 13% of the platform members engaged in the scenarios development were women, respectively in Ghana, Mali and Senegal. In Senegal, the process was facilitated by a woman; in Ghana the platforms intermediaries are from different social groups.', '', '1.00'), ('56', '4', '2015', '24', '50', '39.00', 'In 2015 CCAFS science and engagement processes supported improved policies in 22 countries in all five target regions. Tanzania’s new Environmental Policy and Uganda’s Agricultural Policy and Mechanization Framework were supported. Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania, Botswana and Namibia developed validated CSA framework programs based on CCAFS outputs. Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania integrated CSA into INDCs. Rakai and Luwero districts in Uganda integrated CC priorities in five-year development plans. Tanzania and Ghana Met Services are better meeting climate information needs of smallholder farmers. INDCs were strengthened in Colombia and Costa Rica via scenarios, and Honduras strengthened its NAP for the Agricultural Sector. CCAFS helped achieve the Declaration of Central American Countries supporting CSA announced during COP21. Bangladesh’s NAP for agriculture and seventh Five-Year Plan were supported, as were plans for implementing CSA/CSVs in Madhya Pradesh and Nepal.  CCAFS supported the Cambodia National Assembly on CSA. Investment policies are being formulated for Philippine National Climate Change Action Plans. Vietnam’s INDC for agriculture was supported, and that country’s rice sector restructuring and Myanmar’s CSA strategy (Ministry of Agriculture and Irrigation). Ghana’s national CSA action plan was strengthened. Local policies were refined in Mali and Senegal to integrate CC and food security dimensions. The Senegalese Ministry of Agriculture now uses climate information services to guide annual planning. Burkina Faso developed a new plan for the rural sector (PNSR) using scenarios.  “Competent authority” decrees, new agrobiodiversity policies and/or confirmations of PGRFA in MLS were achieved in Bhutan, Guatemala, Rwanda, Costa Rica, Nepal, Uganda and Burkina Faso.', 'National CSA-FPs are highlighting the integration of gender and youth in developing CSA interventions through value chain integration in EA. Women farmers are being considered explicitly in the development of CIS apps. Gender balance and representation of vulnerable groups have consistently been taken into account in design and implementation of scenarios work. Publications on gender inclusion in CC policy were developed and disseminated to policy makers in Costa Rica, Colombia, Peru and the Philippines. Policy inventories in countries of SA have highlighted missing gender sensitivity in policies for promoting CSA. GSI are major components of plans for scaling up CSA in Nepal. Gender is mainstreamed in Ghana’s national CSA action plan and in the WA CSA alliance. Concerning ITPGRFA/MLS, women’s involvement in national policy processes has been assessed. Studies continue on the differential resilience of (and differential institutional gaps between) women and men in CCAFS sites. Kenya, Colombia and Costa Rica are implementing CSA initiatives and strengthening work on gender and social inclusion, utilising a range of CCAFS gender research and tools. A policy brief, an output of a seminar in March, on supporting women farmers in a changing climate informed the updated UNFCCC guide to the negotiations on agriculture.', null, '4.00'), ('57', '4', '2015', '25', '52', '16.00', 'The UNFCCC Paris agreement provides a framework for investment by national/regional/global organizations in climate-smart food systems. CCAFS worked with policy and research partners towards ensuring that agriculture was not excluded from the agreement. The World Business Council for Sustainable Development developed a CSA Action Plan to serve as a framework for private sector investments in CSA. CCAFS played an important role in the process as a scientific partner. With COMESA, ACPC/UNECA, CORAF/WECARD and IDRC, three submissions to UNFCCC during SBSTA 42 were made by the AGN. CIAT/CCAFS developed a CSA Country Profile for Nicaragua as input to a WB report for Nicaraguan policy makers. CCAFS’s partnership with ASEAN-CRN helped to develop an umbrella program on Climate Change Adaptation and Mitigation (CChaM), a platform for collaborative R&D, knowledge management, and capacity development in SEA.  WWF used CCAFS’s SEA scenarios for an ADB investment study. Scenarios for the Pacific region were developed by CCAFS and partners, to guide regional investments through SPC. UNDP enlisted CCAFS for Bangladesh’s NAP process. IFPRI and partners, via IMPACT modelling, informed policy and investment discussions within OECD and FAO.  WMO, WFP, and ADRA are all directing institutional investments towards climate services for smallholder farmers. Five initiatives are piloting the CCSL M&E framework; partnerships with IIED’s TAMD and DFID’s BRACED programs are highlighting learning in organisational change.  FAO Council adopted CGRFA guidelines in 2015, designed to assist national climate change adaptation planning. CCAFS analyses of INDCs were used as input to the WB\'s Climate Change Action Plan.', 'CCAFS supported the AGN in a submission on the inclusion of gender in CC to the UNFCCC during SBSTA 42. Gender received attention in some 40% of the INDCs submitted ahead of COP21. The WBCSD CSA Action Plan explicitly aims to address gender and social inequality issues, thus ensuring that private sector investments will strive to strengthen gender and social inclusion. Guidelines adopted by the CGRFA recommend that gendered uses of GRFA should be taken into consideration when developing plans for integrating GRFA into national climate change strategies, and that women and marginalized social groups should be represented in processes for the development of those strategies. CCAFS’s Gender and Inclusion Toolkit has been downloaded over 3,200 times, with users in a wide range of countries and organisations (the GSI Toolkit was one of the most popular items in the CCAFS publications repository in 2015). Contributions on gender and youth were made to strengthen the Guide to UNFCCC Negotiations on Agriculture Toolkit for Communications and Outreach, to support UNFCCC processes and feed into COP21. Gender assessment of the INDCs was undertaken.', null, '0.00');
COMMIT;

-- ----------------------------
